<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Reimposes Censorship on Foreign Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka Thursday reimposed
censorship on the Colombo-based foreign media with regard to
reporting of the civil war between government troops and Tamil
Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
The censorship was reimposed as part of the Public Security
Ordinance that was invoked on Wednesday by the government to deal
with a fresh offensive by rebels in the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Under the new regulations, the government has powers to stop
sale and distribution of newspapers seen contravening national
security interests and shut down printing presses.
</P>
<P>
The government last imposed censorship on foreign media in 1998,
but later lifted it. War news in local newspapers is already
censored by the government.
</P>
<P>
The government's move came as the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam rebels have scored stunning victories against government
troops in recent weeks in their push toward Jaffna, their former
stronghold which they lost to government troops in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
