<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Adopt more IT-related Laws: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIANG MAI, Thailand, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will adopt
more information technology-related laws to make the country
better adapted to the information age, Arthit Urairat, science,
technology and environment minister of Thailand, said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar co-organized by the Asian Development
Bank (ADB) and the International Business Machines Corporation,
Arthit said so far Thailand has adopted six IT-related laws,
including electronic transaction act, electronic signature act,
data protection act, electronic funds transfer act, computer crime
act and universal access act.
</P>
<P>
Among them, the electronic transaction law is based on the
United Nations Commission on International Trade Law (UNCITRAL)
model law on electronic commerce and recognizes the validity of
contracts created by electronic communications, the minister
explained, adding that electronic signature law is based on
UNCITRAL draft uniform rules on electronic signatures to provide
the security and authentication of electronic commerce transaction.
</P>
<P>
More new laws related to the regulation of IT industry are in
the process of being drafted, Arthit said.
</P>
<P>
The Internet will have tremendous impact on life, work and
progress of the human being, he said, calling the coming era the
era of "networked and networkable products and services."
</P>
<P>
The Internet can greatly reduce cost of production, make the
global market borderless and timeless and allow easier goods
delivery. "Growth in the future depends on the growth of the
internet," the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
Electronic commerce is considered an important trade strategy
for Thailand and will be included in the ninth and 10th National
Economic and Social Development Plan.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is going to hold the 33rd annual meeting of the board
of governors in Chiang Mai, some 1,000 kilometers north of Bangkok,
from May 6 to May 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
