<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. For Dismantling Pro-Israeli Militia: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Roed Larsen, envoy of the United
Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan, told a press conference here
Friday that the U.N. shares Lebanon's view the pro-Israel South
Lebanon Army (SLA) should be dismantled during the Israeli
withdrawal process.
</P>
<P>
After his third round of meeting with Lebanese leaders, Larsen
stressed that Israel must "cease all communication with the SLA and
the Israeli-allied militia have to give up their heavy weapons."
</P>
<P>
"These are the conditions of the United Nations to verify the
(Israeli) withdrawal" from south Lebanon, said the U.N. deputy
secretary general.
</P>
<P>
Larsen reiterated that Israel should release all Lebanese
detainees in Israeli jails, most of whom being held for years
without trial or even without charges.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the Security Council will decide on the
land dispute between Israel and Lebanon over Shebbaa Farms, adding
that the U.N. will identify the border line.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized Shebbaa Farms during the 1967 Mideast war. The
highly fertile farms are located at the foot of Mount Hermon,
Syria's highest mountain which is now under Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Israel said the farms belong to Syria, and that a withdrawal
from the area would be dealt with in its peace talks with Damascus.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanon argued that the area was transferred to Lebanon in a
1951 agreement between Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Larsen expressed welcome to a joint statement issued Thursday by
foreign ministers of Syria, Egypt and Saudi Arabia, in which they
agreed that U.N. peacekeeping force should be deployed into south
Lebanon after Israel's withdrawal, scheduled by July.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy deplored Israel's repeated attacks on Lebanese
civilians and civil facilities, saying "any attacks against any
civilians are unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Larsen left Beirut later Friday to the village of Nakulla in
south Lebanon to supervise the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon
(UNIFIL) and he will go to Syria on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Larsen is on a two-week Mideast tour starting late April from
Israel. After Syria, he will also visit Jordan and Egypt,
accompanied by a team of political, military and legal advisors.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is expected to decide this month whether to
reinforce or withdraw UNIFIL, based on Larsen's report following
his visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
