<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IPU Calls for Lifting Sanctions, Without Mentioning Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-Parliamentary Union (IPU)
concluded its six-day 103rd conference here on Friday with a call
for lifting all sanctions that most badly affected civilians.
</P>
<P>
The appeal fell short of mentioning Iraq despite intensive
lobbying efforts by the country.
</P>
<P>
As part of a final resolution on world peace, stability, and
development, the IPU requested "the abolition of those types of
sanctions that hit civilians, and especially children, the
hardest," but did not mention the name or cases of any country.
</P>
<P>
During the IPU session, the Iraqi delegation, headed by National
Assembly Speaker Saadoun Hamadi, lobbied hard to draw attention of
the participants to the plight of Iraqi people under the decade-old
international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Hamadi said on different occasions that some 1.5 million Iraqis
died under the embargo, imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait, and now over 7,000 Iraqi children are dying monthly due to
malnutrition or lack of necessary medication.
</P>
<P>
He called the crippling sanctions as a "war of massive
slaughter" that had been more barbarous than weapons of massive
destruction, and urged for a joint Arab action to help end the
ordeal of Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the IPU conference also passed resolutions on the
rights of refugees and the promotion of dialog between different
cultures and civilizations.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva-based IPU was founded in 1889. With 144 members at
present, it makes its biannual conference the largest forum for
international parliamentary diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
Its next session is expected to be held in October in Jakarta,
Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
