<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Phones Syrian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
phoned Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh on Friday over the
recent Israeli air raids on Lebanese infrastructures and the
scheduled Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed appreciation for the joint statement issued
Thursday after a meeting between Shareh and his Egyptian and Saudi
counterparts, Amr Moussa and Prince Saud al-Faisal, in Syria.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers agreed in the statement to hold the United
Nations responsible for the implementation of the U.N. Security
Council Resolutions 425 and 426 through the U.N. mission on the
Lebanese-Israeli borders.
</P>
<P>
Shareh told Annan that Syria was always committed to the U.N.
Charter and U.N. resolutions, pointing out that the Israeli attacks
against Lebanese civil targets triggered the ongoing tension in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Israeli fighter jets launched air raids in the small hours of
Friday on two Lebanese power stations and the Beirut-Damascus
highway, injuring at least dozen Lebanese citizens.
</P>
<P>
Israel said the offensive was a retaliation for the Lebanese
Hezbollah rocket attacks on north Israel mid-Thursday, which killed
an Israeli soldier and wounded another soldier and five civilians.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Thursday evening, Hezbollah claimed
responsibility for the attacks, saying they were avenging the
Israeli attacks that killed two Lebanese civilians Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Roed Larsen, envoy of the United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan, will start his visit to Syria on Saturday as part of his
ongoing Mideast tour that has taken him to Israel and Lebanon and
will also take him to Jordan and Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
