<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State Phones Syrian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright phoned Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh on Friday over
the latest developments in the Middle East and the escalating
tension in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The two sides condemned targeting civilians in both Lebanon and
Israel and urged the warring parties to exercise self-restraint.
</P>
<P>
Shareh asserted that reports verified by Lebanon showed that
Israel was to blame for the recent escalation in south Lebanon, the
Arab-Syrian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Syria is against the escalating tension and the renewed attacks
on Lebanese civilian targets, Shareh told Albright, noting that the
attacks coincided with Israel's talks about its intention to pull
out from south Lebanon by July, ending its 22-year occupation
there.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes bombed two power stations in Lebanon, the
Beirut-Damascus highway and a guerrilla arms depot early Friday in
retaliation for rocket attacks by Lebanese Hezbollah on northern
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The guerillas rocketed northern Israel Thursday afternoon for
the deaths of an 80-year-old woman and her 40-year-old daughter and
Israel's earlier air strikes against the Lebanese civilian targets
which wounded at least 12 Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Expressing deep regret over civilian victims, Albright
reiterated her call on the warring sides to maintain self-
restraint. 
</P>
</TEXT>
