<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Finances Power Project in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) announced Friday that it will invest up to 41
million U.S. dollars in the Kipevu II power project, the first
private power project in Kenya to be financed on a non-recourse
project finance basis.
</P>
<P>
The project, whose total cost is 86 million dollars, will build
a 74 megawatt diesel engine generation plant in Mombasa, Kenya's
main seaport and second largest city. The output will be sold to
Kenya Power &AMP; Lighting Company Ltd., the national publicly listed
electricity utility, through a 20-year power purchase agreement.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has an acute shortage of power, and Kipevu will provide a
much needed stable source of electricity that will contribute to
economic growth, said the IFC, part of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The IFC's financing consists of an equity investment of up to 1.
05 million dollars, a subordinated loan of up to 1.4 million
dollars and a loan of up to 15.1 million dollars for the IFC's own
account. In addition, the IFC was instrumental in arranging
syndicated loans of up to 23.5 million dollars for the account of
participants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
