<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujimori To Win 45 Pct Votes: Polling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Current Peruvian President and
presidential candidate Alberto Fujimori would win the elections in
a second electoral round with 45 percent of the votes, according
to a poll published Friday by the Apoyo firm.
</P>
<P>
The poll, taken at a national level, gives 43 percent of the
voting preferences to opposition candidate Alejandro Toledo,
leader of the Peru Posible party.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori and Toledo will vie in the ballot boxes for the
presidency of Peru in a run-off election on May 28 after none of
them obtained 50 percent of the votes plus one in April 9
elections.
</P>
<P>
The number of persons who will drop a blank ballot represents
four percent of the electors, according to the Apoyo probe, while
eight percent still do not decide whom of the two candidates they
will give their vote to.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian president obtains the bigger electoral acceptance
at the level of the Peruvian capital, with 48 percent of the
suffrages, and the opposition hopeful gets 38 percent of the
preferences.
</P>
<P>
Toledo has first place in other cities of the interior of the
country with 47 percent of the vote against Fujimori's 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Apoyo asked the polled about Fujimori's
credibility and that of Toledo, and the first obtained 49 percent,
while the second got 35 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
