<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges All Sides to Restrain on Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said in a statement
that the conflict could undermine the U.S. peace efforts. "We
deplore the attacks on both sides involving civilians and civilian
facilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply troubled by the recent escalation of violence
and we deeply regret the loss of life, injuries and damage to
infrastructure of both sides," he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright conferred with
Israeli Ambassador David Ivri at a dinner of the American Jewish
Committee Thursday and telephoned Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah guerrillas based in Lebanon shelled northern Israel a
second day Friday. Israeli warplanes blasted power installations
in Beirut and northern Lebanon in response.
</P>
<P>
"The important thing is to get restraint to try to stop the
escalation of violence because that can disrupt the ongoing peace
effort," Boucher told reporters.
</P>
<P>
American mediators Dennis Ross and Aaron Miller are
participating in negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians,
which are due to resume Sunday after a break.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the talks, Boucher said both sides put a variety of
issues on the table and they had serious exchanges on those ideas.
</P>
</TEXT>
