<HEADLINE> Son of Zanzibar's First President Joins Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The son of Zanzibar's first
president Sheikh Abeid Amani Karume on Friday collected
nomination forms to contest for the Isle's presidency with a
package of promises including promotion of reconciliation and
restoration of a normal political life.
</P>
<P>
The 52-year-old Amani Abeid Karume, Zanzibar's Minister for
Communications and Transport, was the second to declare candidacy
in the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM). Deputy Minister for
Finance Abdisalaa Issa Khatibu collected the forms on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, he promised to defend the union
between the Indian Ocean island of Zanzibar and mainland Tanzania
at any cost, saying shortcoming in the union could be ironed out
through proper channels of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, the Secretary-General of the opposition Civic
United Front (CUF) Seif Shariff Hamad declared his intention to
join the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Presidential and parliamentary elections in Zanzibar and
mainland Tanzania are scheduled for October 29, the second
multi-party elections in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
CCM led by Zanzibar's current President Salmin Amour claimed a
narrow victory over the CUF in the 1995 elections, but CUF
questioned the result.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar and Tanganyika formed the United Republic of Tanzania
in 1964 However, the island enjoys autonomous status with its own
government and parliament. 
</P>
