<HEADLINE> Iran's Hard-liner Defends Crackdown on Reformists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A hard-line Iranian official on Friday
defended the recent conservative crackdown on the reformist
campaign, insisting that freedoms should not conflict with Islamic
principles.
</P>
<P>
Social and political freedoms should not be opposed to the
Islamic principles, and the Guardians Council has the
responsibility to guarantee the independence of the Islamic system
and national unity, said Mohammad Yazdi, former judiciary chief.
</P>
<P>
Addressing thousands of worshipers during the weekly
congregational prayers, Yazdi also accused the reformist press of
questioning the Islamic principles and norms and the cleric ruling
of the country.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came after the conservative judiciary jailed several
reformist journalists and ordered the closure of 17 publications
last week, as part of the hard-liners' efforts to curb the
reformist campaign fostered by President Mohammad Khatami since he
took office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the February parliamentary elections, Yazdi said
that monitoring the election process is among the duties of the
conservative-dominated Guardians Council, of which he is a member.
</P>
<P>
Reformists allied with the president won more than two thirds of
the 224 seats decided in the first round of elections, ending long-
time conservative control of the parliament which has stymied much
of Khatami's effort for social and cultural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The election watchdog Guardians Council annulled the results in
several constituencies, depriving nine reformist winners of the
right to enter the new parliament. This move stirred up a series of
protests across the country.
</P>
<P>
The council also keeps on delaying the approval of the election
results in Tehran, the most important constituency where reformists
won 29 of the 30 seats in the first round of elections.
</P>
<P>
On the runoff election which started Friday in 52 constituencies
in 22 provinces, Yazdi said its results would be declared by next
Wednesday so that the new parliament would start work on May 27.
</P>
<P>
The runoff will decide the winners of 66 seats not yet decided
because candidates did not get the minimum 25-percent votes needed
to enter the parliament directly.
</P>
<P>
Only after the runoff will the Guardians Council decide whether
to approve the first round results in Tehran and let the new
parliament start work on time, local reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
