<HEADLINE> Polling Extended in Iran's Parliamentary Runoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The polling for the Iranian
parliamentary runoffs was extended by two hours in all the 52
constituencies due to massive turnout, the Interior Ministry
announced.
</P>
<P>
The voting was scheduled to end at 7 p.m. (1430 GMT) but was
extended to 9 p.m. (1630 GMT), the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The polling started at 9 a.m. (0430 GMT) in 52 constituencies in
22 provinces and some 132 candidates run for the remaining 66 seats
of the 290-seat Majlis (parliament).
</P>
<P>
The result of the runoffs was scheduled to be announced on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reformist allies of President Mohammad Khatami are expected
to repeat the landslide victory in the February polls despite the
conservative crackdown which shut down almost all outspoken
reformist newspapers in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
The reformists took over more than two third of the 224 seats in
the first round, ousting the longtime conservative majority in
parliament that had stymied most of the Khatami's reform programs.
</P>
<P>
But the conservative Guardians Council nullified the results in
52 constituencies, depriving nine reformists of their victory, and
forcing others to the runoffs.
</P>
<P>
It also delayed confirmation of results of Tehran constituency,
the biggest and most important one in which the reformists had won
29 out of the total 30 seats.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that the fate of the first round polls in Tehran
constituency might rely on the result of the runoffs as the
election watchdog Guardians Council claimed it had found errors in
vote counting.
</P>
<P>
The Guardians Council waits to see the result of the runoffs to
decide whether to confirm or nullify the result of Tehran
constituency, political analysts here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
