<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Winds of Change Blow in Turkish Presidential Election by Huai Chengbo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the three rounds of ballots held in the parliament, Sezer,
the presiding judge of the Constitutional Court, won 281, 314 and
330 votes respectively, beating all his rivals, including the
Parliament Speaker Yildirim Akbulut.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has arrived at a crossroads of development at the turn of
century. Its being accepted as a candidate for membership of the
European Union last November has tremendously inspired the people.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing President Suleyman Demirel declared toward the end of
1999 that "Turkey will face a bright future and assume a place as
one of the major developed countries of the world (in the new
century)." To achieve this end, stability and change are two
things that people always have in mind.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, the parliament refused to go along with the demands
of the leaders of the tripartite coalition government to extend the
tenure of Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Although the 76-year-old statesman, if still in office, would
serve as a guarantee of stability, many deputies contended that to
maintain stability was not Demirel's patent.
</P>
<P>
The deputies, aware of the general demand for change in the
country, have instead accepted Sezer, the joint candidate of
leaders of the three ruling parties and two opposition parties, as
the new president.
</P>
<P>
A poll showed that there is a general public approval for Sezer
despite he is from outside the parliament. It appears that Sezer is
widely regarded as a symbol of democratization and reform.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that those who opposed him have gone to great
lengths trying, without success so far, to find something to
crucify him with.
</P>
<P>
"As a dignified jurist, Sezer will go to the presidential
mansion as a man who enjoys the trust of citizens with a wide
variety of political views," commented Milliyet (National), a major
Turkish newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Sezer will take over the presidency from Demirel on May 16.
</P>
<P>
With so many people applauding, it is a good beginning for his
political career. But in the long-run, the judge-turned political
leader may find it harder to run a country than handle a case.
</P>
<P>
There is a long way to go. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
