<HEADLINE> Israeli Bombing Costs Power Plant Millions of Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Baddawi power plant in Tripoli,
northern Lebanon, was pulverized thoroughly in early Friday's
Israeli air raid, suffering a loss of millions of U.S. dollars,
Voice of Lebanon Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
George Mouawad, chairman of Lebanon's state-run Electricite du
Liban (EDL), was quoted as saying that the generating plant, the
relay stations and all high-voltage lines were completely
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Rebuilding the Baddawi facility would take at least two years,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel's 45-minute air strikes began at 2:45 Friday morning
(0045 GMT), targeting the Basleem power relay station in the
capital city of Beirut, Tripoli's suburban power plant of Baddawi,
a gas filling station in the Bekaa Valley town of Brital, a
Hezbollah arms depot near Baalbek and the Beirut-Damascus highway.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli attacks were a retaliation for Lebanese Hezbollah
guerrillas' Katyusha rocket attacks on northern Israel late
Thursday, in which one Israeli solider was killed and several
civilians injured.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah fighters were avenging Thursday morning's Israeli air
raids on south Lebanon which killed an 80-year-old Lebanese woman
and her daughter.
</P>
<P>
Parts of Tripoli and Beirut were blacked out after Friday's
Israeli attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese police said the Basleem station was hit twice by
Israeli jets in low-flying missile-shooting runs that jolted many
Beirut residents out of bed. An eyewitness was quoted as saying the
Basleem plant was now "a wreck."
</P>
<P>
It was the second time in three months that Israel bombed power
stations in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli jet fighters pounded three Lebanese power stations on
February 8, causing widespread power outage and wounding at least
20 civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
