<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IPU Backs Palestinian Refugees` Right to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The 144-member Inter-Parliamentary
Union (IPU) on Friday expressed support for the right of
Palestinian refugees to return to their homeland in an apparent
victory for the Arab bloc at the end of the 103th IPU conference in
Amman.
</P>
<P>
In one of its final resolutions of the conference, the IPU also
voiced its strong support for all efforts leading to a just,
durable and comprehensive peace in the Middle East, and for the
famous "land for peace" principle guiding the peace process between
Israel and its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, proposed by the German delegation, called for
the Jewish state to comply with U.N. resolution 194, which said the
Palestinian refugees should be allowed to return home.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are over 3 million Palestinian refugees who are
taking shelter in Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and other countries after
they fled their home because of the creation of Israel in 1948 and
successive wars between Israel and Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Though outvoted, the Israeli delegates had also proposed their
own version on the Palestinian refugee issue, but only mentioned
a "just solution to the problem of Palestinian refugees" without a
specific reference to the U.N. Resolution 194.
</P>
<P>
The resolution marked an apparent victory for Arab
parliamentarians who had conducted a heated debate with their
Israeli counterparts and Israel`s supporters during the six-day
session.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians from Egyptian, Iraqi and Syrian and other Arab
countries had taken to the podium, accusing Israel of trying to
deprive the Palestinians of their rights to return to their home.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the refugee issue, the IPU conference also adopted
two final resolutions on ways of promoting world peace, stability
and development as well as promoting dialog between different
cultures and civilizations.
</P>
<P>
A record 1,400 representatives from 128 parliaments and over 20
international organizations had participated the conference in
Amman.
</P>
<P>
The 103rd IPU was opened here on Sunday by Jordanian King
Abdullah Bin Hussein and its next session is expected to take place
in Jakarta, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The IPU, founded in 1889 and now with 144 members, is the
largest international parliamentary organization, and its biannual
conferences serves as the biggest venue for parliamentary
diplomacy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
