<HEADLINE> Russia Strengthens Chechnya Security for Victory Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia's federal forces have beefed
up security regime in Chechnya for fear that rebels may conduct a
number of subversive and terrorist acts during the forthcoming
Victory Day celebrations, Interfax reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
May 9th will mark the 55th anniversary of the anti-fascism war
victory in Russia. According to the Russian federal forces'
command, "during the upcoming Victory Day holidays the bandits
intend to organize a number of subversive acts at military and
civil facilities in Chechnya, especially in Grozny and other
heavily populated areas."
</P>
<P>
"To prevent provocative acts by the extremists, the command of
the Interior Ministry grouping in Chechnya has taken additional
security measures," said the command.
</P>
<P>
Driving restrictions have been tightened in the republic and
additional checks at the checkpoints, including those along the
Chechen administrative border, are now being conducted, the
military said.
</P>
<P>
The federal block-posts have been reinforced in regions where
the situation remains complicated. The temporary police stations,
especially those in southern and southeastern districts of
Chechnya, have been strengthened to conduct preventative
operations.
</P>
<P>
The special operations to search and destroy the dispersed
guerrilla bands, their bases and arms and ammunition caches in
mountainous and foothill areas of Chechnya will not be suspended
during the holidays, the military said.
</P>
<P>
"Close interaction has been established between defense and
interior ministry units and other armed structures operating in
Chechnya in order to react swiftly to possible threats from bandit
formations," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, another Interfax report said rebels made a new attack
on a federal convoy in Chechnya Friday and from one to three
Russian servicemen were killed.
</P>
<P>
According to the command of the eastern grouping of the Russian
forces, rebels only opened fire on the last vehicle in the convoy
in the area of Serzhen-Yurt because they were few in number and
could not stage a large-scale attack.
</P>
<P>
The command said federal troops promptly repelled the attackers
through concerted actions.
</P>
<P>
But Kremlin spokesman on Chechnya Sergei Yastrzhembsky denied
the report, admitting that there were clashes Friday in Serzhen-
Yurt, where rebels opened fire on federal intelligence officers in
cars.
</P>
<P>
"One serviceman was killed and another was wounded and his life
is out of danger," while four bodies of rebels were discovered at
the clash site, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
