<HEADLINE> Russia to Impose Direct Federal Rule on Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Moscow will introduce direct federal
rather than direct presidential rule in the republic of Chechnya
by the end of this month, Russian Deputy Prime Minister Nikolai
Koshman told the press Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under federal rule, territorial departments of federal
ministries will be set up in Chechnya for two to three years, said
Koshman, who is also the cabinet's envoy in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Initially, two or three officials of every ministry will work
on the department boards. They will select the personnel from
local population. The territorial boards will eventually become
local authorities in Chechnya, he said.
</P>
<P>
A Russian State Duma (lower house of parliament) member will be
elected in Chechnya on August 20, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the federal parliamentary elections were not
held in the single-mandate constituency of Chechnya due to the
anti-terrorist campaign there.
</P>
<P>
However, the elections of the Chechen president cannot be held
in the republic sooner than at the end of 2001 or early 2002,
Koshman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
