<HEADLINE> Belarus, Russia Can Form Union Army Grouping: Lukashenko </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Belarus President Alexander
Lukashenko said Friday that his country and Russia may create a
combined army grouping to strengthen the security of the Belarus-
Russia Union State on the Western front.
</P>
<P>
The Belarus armed forces can be reinforced by a group of
Russian troops and the creation of a united grouping is possible
in the event of a military conflict or its threat, Lukashenko told
an interview with the Russian newspaper Krasnaya Zvezda (Red Star).
</P>
<P>
"In this case, we would deploy the Belarussian army and back it
with units from Russia's western regions as a second echelon," but
"in peacetime, we do not intend to bolster anything," Lukashenko
said.
</P>
<P>
The reason for backing the Belarus army with Russian units,
according to Lukashenko, is NATO's military presence in Europe. "
What they have there is not 300,000 but a million, trained, and
armed servicemen, so we will not defend ourselves on our own," the
president stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Belarus-Russian united army grouping will probably consist
of 500,000 soldiers rather than 300,000, which will be discussed
at a meeting of the Supreme State Committee of the Belarus-Russian
Union due in May, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
