<HEADLINE> U.N. Estimates 318 Staff Held in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- As many as 318 U.N. staff may
now be taken hostage by rebels in Sierra Leone, a U.N. spokesman
said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press conference that no
new fighting had been reported but there had been reports of
movement by the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) rebels, possibly
involving the use of U.N. armored personnel carriers captured from
peacekeeping forces they detained.
</P>
<P>
"The number of detentions of U.N. personnel by the RUF,
meanwhile, continues to climb," he said. "The latest estimate
could be as high as 318."
</P>
<P>
The latest figure included 92 personnel reportedly detained
Thursday, minus four crew members and two passengers of a
helicopter who were released earlier Friday, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, approximately 208 members of the Zambian
contingent which were on their way to Makeni and with whom the U.N.
mission had lost radio contact yesterday, were disarmed and
detained by the RUF," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And 24 other U.N. personnel are being held in Kailahun,"
Eckhard said. Meanwhile, a Nigerian contingent of more than 100 U.
N. peacekeepers were also detained "but later released, minus
their weapons."  
</P>
</TEXT>
