<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Calls on Uganda, Rwanda to Immediately End Fighting in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday adopted a presidential statement, calling on Ugandan and
Rwandan forces to immediately end their fighting in Kisangani in
the northern part of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The Security Council, expressing its "grave concern" at the
renewed fighting, "condemns unreservedly the outbreak of military
hostilities in Kisangani," the statement said. "This renewed
fighting (is), once more, threatening the implementation of the
Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement."
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council demands that these latest hostilities
cease immediately and that those involved in the fighting at
Kisangani reaffirm their commitment to the Lusaka process and
comply with all relevant Security Council resolutions," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation Security Council adopted the presidential
statement at the end of the four-hour closed-door meeting,
beginning Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
"The Council is also concerned by reports of the killing of
innocent Congolese civilians," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also reaffirmed its commitment to the
national sovereignty, territorial integrity, and political
independence of the DRC, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops clashed in the DRC before dawn
Friday in Kisangani, killing five civilians and wounding nine in a
burst of shelling and gunfire, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The latest fighting took place as a U.N. Security Council
mission is visiting the DRC and the capitals of the countries
involved in the many-sided conflict in the central African country.
The visit is intended to secure agreement to the deployment of the
U.N. peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda have been long backing rebels in the DRC to
fight the government headed by President Laurent Kabila, supported
by Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, in the nation's long-standing
armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In a peace agreement signed last August and renewed in mid-
April this year, the warring sides committed to a cease-fire. They
said they would let the United Nations deploy a 5,500-member U.N.
peacekeeping mission in the DRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
