<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets Japanese Prime Minister for G-8 Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the one-hour and 15-minute meeting, the two leaders also
discussed the recovery of Japan's economy. Clinton said
information technology can be a growth stimulus for Japan.
</P>
<P>
"They spent most of their time talking about the upcoming G-8
summit," a senior administration official told reporters at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
Describing the meeting as "warm, cordial, convivial," the
senior official said, "The prime minister spent a fair amount of
time helping the president understand the special significance of
Okinawa, and the reasons why the Japanese government favored
holding the summit on the island."
</P>
<P>
Clinton will be the first U.S. president to visit Okinawa since
America relinquished the island's postwar administration to Japan
in 1972.
</P>
<P>
U.S. military bases on Okinawa are a source of friction for
residents, who have been angry at the American presence there
since two Marines and a sailor raped a local schoolgirl in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The small island houses about two-thirds of the more than 50,
000 U.S. military personnel stationed in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the meeting started, Clinton said he hopes to
speak with the residents there. "I want to talk to the prime
minister about how we should do that."
</P>
<P>
"But we tried to be sensitive to the concerns of the people and
to be highly respectful. And where mistakes have been made, we've
tried to correct them and we will continue to do that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Mori talked about the agenda for the G-8 summit,
which is to be attended by leaders from Britain, Canada, France,
Italy, the U.S., Japan, Germany and Russia. The agenda includes
health issues, vaccines, education, poverty, and information
technology, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton shared the experience in the United States in economic
development. In Japan only 35 percent of Japanese schoolchildren
have access to the Internet, but in the United States, it's 95
percent, the official added.
</P>
<P>
"So in that context of the importance that information
technology has, as we've seen in our country how important
information technology is -- to spur economic growth, create jobs,
create wealth -- we believe that this is something that can be of
great interest and significance for the Japanese people," the
official added. 
</P>
