<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mbeki Backs Zimbabwe's Land Distribution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 5 (Xinhua) (C South African President Thabo Mbeki
Friday supported the redistribution of land among the
dispossessed black people of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the Zimbabwe International trade Fair in
Bulawayo, the country's second largest city, Mbeki said South
Africa was also hopeful that the land question in Zimbabwe, which
has seen the invasion of about 1,000 white owned commercial farms
by war veterans and land-hungry peasants, would be resolved
successfully in a non-confrontational manner.
</P>
<P>
He said both South Africa and Zimbabwe, which experienced
extensive land dispossession of the indigenous majority by
colonizer, were confronted by the challenge to resolve this
colonial legacy.
</P>
<P>
"Our peoples, on both banks of the Limpopo River, both black
and white, have a responsibility to recognize the fact that the
land question constitutes an important part of the national
agenda," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Accordingly, they must commit themselves to work together to
resolve this central question. To advance the common good," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africans were convinced that it would be in the
best interest if the land question in Zimbabwe was dealt with in
a cooperative and non-confrontational manner among all
Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
"Accordingly, we trust that ways and means will be found to end
the conflict that has erupted in some areas of Zimbabwe,
occasioned by the still unresolved land question in the country,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who also paid tribute for the role Zimbabwe took in the
fight against apartheid, said peace, stability, democracy and
social progress in Zimbabwe were as important for the country as
they were for the rest of the region.
</P>
<P>
"We know from our history that you are ready to assist us to
achieve peace, stability, democracy and social progress in our
own country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So are we, in the common interest, willing and ready to work
with you for peace, stability, democracy and social progress in
Zimbabwe, in our region and the rest of our continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said land redistribution in both Zimbabwe and South
Africa, also imposes the obligation to ensure that such land was
used productively to help provide a better life for the ordinary
people.
</P>
<P>
He said it was inevitable that any resettlement program must be
 accompanied by investment in agricultural development as well as
the rural social and economic infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"Our economies must therefore generate the necessary resources
to ensure that this happens," said the South African president.
</P>
</TEXT>
