<HEADLINE> Rand Rebounds on Profit Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The embattled rand clawed back
early losses and managed to end the day six cents off its
intraday worst level on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was last quoted at 6.9680 to one U.S.
dollar, weaker than its previous close 6.8760, but off its
intraday worst level of 7.0300.
</P>
<P>
The rand hit new record lows against the dollar early in the
trading session and continued to hover at around historic lows
for much of the day.
</P>
<P>
"Pre-weekend short profit-taking and a rebound in the
euro/dollar propelled it off its fresh lifetime low of 7.0300," a
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The dealer said the euro staged a slight recovery against the
dollar and that had aided the rand's recovery.
</P>
<P>
"In light of recent events surrounding the onslaught on rand
and the euro, local and offshore investors are looking for a
safe-haven currency and the US dollar seems to have been the
main successor," another trader said.
</P>
<P>
A state-of-the-nation speech by South African President Thabo
Mbeki on Thursday, in which he had been seen to be adopting a
"rather soft" stance on Zimbabwe, had also not helped, dealers
added.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki took pains on South African television on Thursday to
allay concerns that his government has been covertly backing
invasions of white farms in Zimbabwe by praising white South
African farmers and by indicating that the South African media
haven't fully reported his previous statements on the Zimbabwean
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
