<HEADLINE> S.African President Urges for Stronger Ties With Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 5 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo Mbeki
Friday urged the people of Zimbabwe and South Africa to work
together in building on the victory of the anti-colonial and
anti-racist struggle.
</P>
<P>
He said as neighbors who shared the same trenches in the common
struggle for freedom it was important that the two countries
should work together.
</P>
<P>
The president was officially opening the Zimbabwe International
Trade Fair in Bulawayo, the country's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Practically, together we must decide what we have to
do, again sharing a common trench of struggle to address an
agenda which among other things includes overcoming the legacy of
colonialism and apartheid."
</P>
<P>
He said other things which needed to be resolved were the
achievement of a better life for the masses and expedition of the
process of balanced and mutual regional integration. "We also
need to protect the achievements we have scored so far to ensure
that ours is a region of freedom, democracy, peace and stability,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was important through using the instrument of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) to speed up the
process of the economic integration of the region.
</P>
<P>
"More importantly, we have to ensure that the SADC protocol
comes into force during this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said although there was a gross trade imbalance between
Zimbabwe and South Africa, which was in favor of his country, he
still believed that the two countries still shared a common
obligation of helping to drive the growth of the other economies
in the region. "But without peace and stability we cannot achieve
sustained development," he stressed. 
</P>
