<HEADLINE> Mozambique Expects to Receive More Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano
said here on Friday that the sum of 452.9 million U.S. dollars
pledged at a donors conference in Rome to assist flood-ravaged
Mozambique was not the final figure since other donors had
promised to declare their contributions later.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also expressed satisfaction with the response from the
 international community, saying that the amount promised exceeded
450 million dollars Mozambique had initially requested.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference on his return from Italy,
Chissano said that even some of those countries that made pledges
during the Rome conference on Thursday said they are prepared to
grant additional amounts if the need arises.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on the assurance of transparency in the
use of the funds granted by the donors, Chissano said that
Mozambique prepared the reconstruction program in cooperation with
the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and various donor
organizations.
</P>
<P>
"It was the UNDP that suggested that the money be channeled to
the Bank of Mozambique (the Mozambican Central Bank), which shows
confidence in the Mozambican government. This is an
acknowledgement that Mozambique knows how to use the funds", said
Chissano.
</P>
<P>
On reconstruction priorities, Chissano explained that all
sectors are equal in priority, and thus work will start
simultaneously in all sectors.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that there may be cases where a certain donor
stipulates that the money must be used on a specific project, and
Mozambique would respect such conditions. 
