<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Condemns Israeli Bombing of Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid on Friday condemned the latest Israeli
bombing raids on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said in an interview that the Lebanese resistance
against Israel's occupation in south Lebanon is legitimate and
should be supported.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief said Israel should withdraw from south Lebanon as
well as the Golan Heights, which it seized from Syria in 1967,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The pan-Arab bloc will hold an emergency meeting Saturday
afternoon at the level of permanent delegates to discuss the
Israeli attacks, Abdel-Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the escalation of Israeli military attacks on
Lebanon would adversely affect the stability of the area.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes bombed two power stations in Lebanon and a
guerrilla ammunition depot in retaliation for rocket attacks by
Lebanese Hezbollah on northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah rocketed northern Israel Thursday afternoon for the
deaths of an 80-year-old woman and her 40-year-old daughter and
Israel's earlier air strikes against the Lebanese civilian targets
which wounded at least 12 Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, is the main Lebanese military group
fighting against the Israeli occupation of south Lebanon. 
