<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets Japanese Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at a photo opportunity, Clinton expressed
his hope that Japan would continue to rebuild rapidly, relying on
the "inherent strengths" of a highly skilled, educated work force.
</P>
<P>
"We support a strong Japanese economy. I think there are a lot
of inherent strengths in the economy, most of all in the people
and the level of skill and education and capacity to grow," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's getting better... I believe that they will return
to big growth, I hope sooner rather than later," Clinton told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Mori are also discussing the summit of the Group of
Eight in Okinawa, Japan, scheduled in July. Clinton will be the
first U.S. president to visit Okinawa since America relinquished
the island's postwar administration to Japan in 1972.
</P>
<P>
U.S. military bases on Okinawa are a source of friction for
residents, who have been angry at the American presence there
since two Marines and a sailor raped a local schoolgirl in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The small island houses about two-thirds of the more than 50,
000 U.S. military personnel stationed in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he hopes to speak with the residents there. "I
want to talk to the prime minister about how we should do that."
</P>
<P>
"But we tried to be sensitive to the concerns of the people and
to be highly respectful. And where mistakes have been made, we've
tried to correct them and we will continue to do that," he said.
</P>
