<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Love Bug Hit 46,000 Government Computers in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- At least 46,000 government computers
of Canada have been hit since early Thursday morning by an e-mail
worm virus called "ILOVEYOU," local reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The worldwide strike by the love bug affected key Canadian
departments ranging from Canada Customs to Statistics Canada,
leaving countless e-mails sitting unanswered.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the government has been hit hard by an
Internet virus, according to Canadian Industry Minister John
Manley, whose department reported 6,000 computers being affected
Thursday, with normal daily traffic of more than 100,000 e-mail
messages coming to a dead halt.
</P>
<P>
Although many organizations were reported to have a handle on
the problem by the end of Thursday, the love bug is expected to
continue its rampage Friday.
</P>
<P>
The federal government has asked computer experts to contact
local governments across Canada to eradicate the virus, which
already affected one of the largest companies, J.D. Irving Ltd.,
Thursday in the eastern province of New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
While describing the situation as "a Pearl Harbor attack,"
Canadian government officials believe there have been no critical
functions ever hampered.
</P>
<P>
There has been a tiny fraction actually infected and there have
been no major problems reported beyond the lost computer access,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
The virus has affected 270,000 computers worldwide and has
caused the damage of up to 1 billion U.S. dollars in North America.
</P>
<P>
It deletes image and music files, including the popular MP3s.
It also installs a file in the user's local drive that appears to
scan the drive looking for network passwords before sending these
passwords elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
