<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Chief Reassures Public on Euro Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Wim Duisenberg, head of the
European Central Bank (ECB), issued an unusual statement on Friday
reassuring the public about the single currency.
</P>
<P>
Duisenberg said in the statement, directed more to the general
public than to the financial market, that consumers should not
worry about the euro's recent decline.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the European Central Bank would "continue to
do all it can" to control inflation.
</P>
<P>
"I understand their concerns, since a persistently lower euro
exchange rate might ultimately lead to higher prices in the shops,
" said the European central banker in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
"It may also undermine the perception of the euro as a stable
currency."
</P>
<P>
The Dutchman said that the ECB has over the past six months
taken measures to counter risks to price stability and the bank
has increased its benchmark lending interest rates four times
already.
</P>
<P>
"It (the bank) will continue to do all it can to maintain price
stability in the euro area," said Duisenberg.
</P>
<P>
The statement came one day after the euro exchange rate against
the U.S. dollar plunged to an all-time low of 0.8845 dollar. The
single currency for 11 European Union member states has seen a
steady decline since peaking at 1.18 dollars just after the euro's
debut on January 1 last year.
</P>
<P>
The euro exchange rate against the dollar has since dropped by
23 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
