<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sezer Elected New Turkish President in Third Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Ahmet Necdet Sezer, presiding judge of
the Constitutional Court, was elected the 10th president of Turkey
with 330 votes in the third round of balloting Friday.
</P>
<P>
He garnered three-fifths of the votes in the 550-seat
parliament, far more than the 276 votes required in the third round
to become the president.
</P>
<P>
As the joint candidate of the three ruling parties and two main
opposition parties represented in parliament, Sezer had been
considered the favorite for presidency and stood good chance to
win.
</P>
<P>
Ten candidates were competing in the race in the first round of
voting on April 27. Three of them dropped out before the second
ballot.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of Grand National Assembly (parliament) Yidirim Akbulut,
who was once seen as the strongest challenger for Sezer, decided to
give up before the third round, clearing the way for Sezer.
</P>
<P>
Sezer has been leading with an outstanding advantage over all
other competitors throughout the three rounds of balloting in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
During the first two rounds, Sezer took the lead with 281 and
314 votes respectively, short of the two-thirds majority of 367
required to be elected in these two rounds but far exceeding his
nearest rivals.
</P>
<P>
Sezer was seen as a staunch advocator of democratic reforms,
which are essential to Turkey's aspiration of joining the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
The president-elect was born in western Afyon province on
September 13, 1941. He graduated from Afyon High School in 1958 and
Ankara University's School of Law in 1962.
</P>
<P>
The career lawyer was assigned as a member of the Constitutional
Court in 1988 and voted head of the court 10 years later.
</P>
<P>
Soon after taking the position, he banned the Islam-based
Welfare Party for attempting to overthrow the secular order. But he
has called for the 1982 Constitution drawn up under army rule to be
overhauled.
</P>
<P>
Recently, he said that "Turkey must make the necessary changes
to its law and Constitution so as to conform to the universal
standards in the field of human rights."
</P>
<P>
Sezer will take over the presidency in an inauguration ceremony
to be held on May 16 when the outgoing President Suleyman Demirel's
tenure expires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Turkish President-Elect Ahmet Necdet Sezer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The following is the curriculum vitae
of Turkish President-elect Ahmet Necdet Sezer.
</P>
<P>
Sezer was born in Afyon, southwest of capital Ankara, on
September 13, 1941.
</P>
<P>
He graduated from Afyon High School in 1958 and received higher
education at Ankara University's School of Law and graduated in
1962.
</P>
<P>
Sezer completed his compulsory military service at the Military
Academy as a reserve officer, following which he was assigned
judiciary duties, first in Dicle and later in Yerkoy. He was later
assigned to the Court of Cassation as a member of an investigative
panel.
</P>
<P>
After furthering his education at the Ankara Law School in 1977
and 1978, Sezer received his master's degree as a member of the
judges' panel at the Court of Cassation.
</P>
<P>
While serving as a member of the Second Legal Chamber at the
Court of Cassation, Sezer was selected by Turkish president from
three candidates and on September 27, 1988, was assigned as a
member of the Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
On January 6, 1998, Sezer was voted head of the Constitutional
Court.
</P>
<P>
Sezer was a father of three children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
