<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Hsien Loong Praises Role of Clan Associations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Deputy Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong affirmed Friday that "clan associations have
played an important role in Singapore's development from a migrant
colony to an industrial nation" and "continue to play an important
role" in the country's modern society.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister made the remarks at the 15th
anniversary dinner of the Singapore Federation of Chinese Clan
Associations (SFCCA).
</P>
<P>
He said that in the uncertain and difficult conditions of the
early days of Singapore's history, clan associations provided
important life rafts for the many Chinese migrants who came to
Singapore in pursuit of a better life and played an important role
in strengthening bonds between fellow migrants from the same
village or clan, offering support, companionship and practical
help.
</P>
<P>
Lee said clan associations still have a role to play in modern
Singapore against a drastic change in backdrop although
Singaporeans are now enjoying the benefits of fast growing economy,
better living standard, ownership of substantial assets and many
organizations have sprouted up to carry out functions similar to
those of clan associations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to great challenges facing SFCCA in the knowledge era
such as global competition, skills retraining and upgrading,
integration of new arrivals and the moderation of widening income
disparities, Lee emphasized that clan associations continue to
play an important role in Singapore society because people need
mutual support and fellowship and seek stable references to
emotionally anchor themselves during such time of great change and
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
He urged clan associations to help their members adapt to the
changing environment, preserve the core Chinese values and
heritages, engage the younger generations of Singaporeans, induct
fresh blood into their leadership ranks and upgrade their
organizational capabilities.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 300 clan associations in Singapore, 189
of which have affiliated themselves with the SFCCA which was set
up in early 1986 as the leading body of clan associations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
