<HEADLINE> S. Africa Refuses to Pay Philippine Hostage Takers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will oppose the
payment of an apparent 18 million rand (about 2.4 million U.S.
dollars) ransom demand for the release of two South Africans being
held hostage in the Philippines, a senior government official said
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Principally we are opposed to ransom payments. You will only
encourage others to do the same," said Deputy Director-General of
South African Foreign Affairs Department Jerry Matsila in
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
According to Matsila, indirect information indicated that the
abductors wanted 2.4 million U.S. dollars from the Philippine
government for the release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The latest demands of the hostage takers pertained more to
local politics, he said.
</P>
<P>
Muslim extremists captured two South Africans, Carel Strydom
and his wife, in an armed raid on a Malaysian resort island on
Easter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Also taken hostages were nine Malaysians, three Germans, two
French, two Finns, two Filipinos and a Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
The hostages have been taken to the southern Philippine island
of Jolo where they are being held in a reed hut in a rebel camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
