<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Launches Out-of-Court Settlement for Consumer Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on Friday
launched a pan-European network for out-of-court settlement of
consumer disputes.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of the extra-judicial network was hailed as an
important initiative toward creating an effective and practical
environment to boost consumer confidence in cross-border
transactions and trade, especially in the ever growing sector of e-
commerce.
</P>
<P>
"The European extra-judicial network marks an important
milestone to give consumers access to simple, low cost and
effective means of resolving cross-border conflicts," said David
Byrne, EU commissioner for consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
The network will cover any consumer dispute over goods and
services. Problems over deliveries, defective products, or
products or services that do not fit consumers' description will
be dealt with by a single, one-stop national contact point in each
EU member state.
</P>
<P>
The contact point or "clearing house" as it will be called will
help the dissatisfied consumer with information and support in
making a claim to the out-of-court dispute resolution system in
the country where supplier of the products or services is located.
</P>
<P>
This network of clearing houses will be operational by the
second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Resorts to traditional litigation are neither practical nor
cost effective for consumers and businesses alike. The newly
introduced dispute settlement network can reduce costs,
formalities, time and such obstacles as language problems in cross-
border disputes by offering consumers easy access.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner called on the EU member states to commit funds
for building the clearing houses "as quickly as possible."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
