<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Working to Resolve Hostage Incidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MANILA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
re-assured the public Friday that his government is doing
everything necessary to free the hostages in Basilan and Sulu
kidnapped by Abu Sayyaf extremists.
</P>
<P>
The president also expressed his deepest sympathy to the
families of four hostages in Basilan executed and tortured by the
Abu Sayyaf extremists as well as to the kin of the victims,
including soldiers ad civilians, killed in isolated clashes
between the military and rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
He called on the kidnappers to immediately release their
captives, a gesture, which, he said, is not only humane but
practical.
</P>
<P>
"I condole with the families of the victims of this latest
conflict. I sympathize with those who have been injured and to
many more who have been displaced," he told reporters at the
Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
"As for the remaining hostages in Basilan and Sulu, I pledge
that the government will do everything necessary to resolve the
problem and save them at the soonest," he added.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen hostages, mostly children, have already been rescued
by the military during operations in Basilan. The Abu Sayyaf
tortured and killed four of the adult hostages, including a priest,
before fleeing with their remaining captives.
</P>
<P>
Another set of hostages, mostly foreigners, are now holed up
with their kidnappers in Jolo island in Sulu. The hostages include
a Filipino, 10 Malaysians, three Germans, two French nationals,
two South Africans, two Finns, and one Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
The military has already cordoned off the area to prevent the
kidnappers from escaping. Negotiations led by Governor Nur Misuari
of the Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao are now being
conducted to secure the hostages' safe release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lankan Troops Foil Rebel Attempts in Jaffna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan government troops Friday
managed to foil several attempts by rebels of Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) to infiltrate the defense lines in the
northern Jaffna peninsula, an official report declared.
</P>
<P>
"LTTE terrorists made several abortive attempts to push back
troops from their forward-defended localities in general area
south of Kilali. Troops supported by artillery and mortar fire
effectively repulsed all terrorist attempts compelling them to
withdraw southward," the government's Special Media Information
Center said in its situation report.
</P>
<P>
It said that two soldiers were killed and another wounded in
the exchange of mortar fire, while 458 LTTE rebels were been
killed between April 27 and May 4.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, fighting for an independent homeland for
minority Tamils in the country's north and east since 1983, have
scored a series of stunning victories since late April and
threatened to recapture Jaffna town, the cultural center of Sri
Lanka's minority Tamils and former stronghold of LTTE rebels which
they lost to government troops in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The report said government troops were in a stronger position
after their April 22 pull out from Elephant Pass, a strategic
causeway linking Jaffna peninsula and the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
The government set up the Special Media Information Center
after it imposed censorship Thursday on the Colombo-based foreign
media with regard to reporting of the civil war between government
troops and LTTE rebels.
</P>
<P>
Invoking the Public Security Act, the entire Sri Lankan nation
was mobilized on Wednesday on a war footing to deal with LTTE
attempts to retake Jaffna town.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have neither responded to the government's
declaration of being on a war footing nor to the claim of
casualties for the last few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
