<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistan Railway is taking
emergency measures for supply of water to drought hit areas of
Baluchistan province on the directive of Chief Executive General
Pervez Musharraf, the Associated Press of Pakistan reported on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the Railway has supplied 45 wagons with water
carriers which have reached Quetta railway station in the
provincial capital on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The first "Water train" will leave for the affected areas on
Friday with each water wagon carrying about 25,000 to 30,000
liters of water.
</P>
<P>
The train will travel on Naushki-Kundi section of the
identified areas providing supplies at different locations.
</P>
<P>
According to railway sources, three water trains a week will be
run from Quetta to drought-hit areas of Baluchistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the Pakistan Railway is also making available 2-3
locomotives as well for running its water trains to Baluchistan's
drought-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
The Railway is also in contact with the Baluchistan Relief
Commissioner and Administration as well for the arrangements it
was making for supply of water. 
</P>
