<HEADLINE> U.N. Urged to Send Peacekeeping Forces to Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council has been
urged to send peacekeeping forces to the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) immediately.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Institute of United Nations seminar on the
theme "Status of Economic Development and the United Nations
System" in Lusaka on Friday, Ambassador of Egypt to Zambia Abdel
Ghaffar Eldib accused the Security Council of failing to implement
the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
That's why it has taken long to send the 5,500-personnel troops
to that country, he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the United Nations to honor the cease-fire agreement
signed last July in Lusaka by all parties involved in the crisis
so that peace can be restored in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
"How can African countries benefit from the United Nations if
it fails to help them in solving their problems like war within
that country?" he said.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador also urged the United Nations to fully support
the economic development for African countries so that the living
standards in the continent can be improved in all aspects.
</P>
<P>
Africa should get united so that they can create one strong
body and speak in one voice at the United Nations meetings, Eldib
said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA) and the Southern African Development Community (SADC),
the ambassador said the two regional organizations should work
together towards the improvement of the economic development in
Africa so that their members can benefit from them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
