<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Trial Questions Scottish Police Officer over Bomb Devices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, The Netherlands, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Testimony at the
Lockerbie trial on Friday related for the first time to the
explosive device that caused the mid-air bombing of the Pan Am
Flight 103 killing 259 people aboard and 11 others on the ground.
</P>
<P>
A Scottish police officer was questioned by the prosecutor and
then cross-questioned by the defense lawyers about the bomb and
its detonator.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Ferrie, a detective chief inspector at the time of the
bombing, gave testimony about the scene that his men witnessed as
the day broke on December 22, 1988, some 12 hours after the Boeing
747 plunged to the ground in pieces in a blaze of fire.
</P>
<P>
He also told the court that the police initially focused the
inquiry on Palestinian organizations.
</P>
<P>
The New York-bound airliner exploded in mid-air and crashed to
the ground from 10,000 meters, wiping out a street of the town.
</P>
<P>
Two Libyans, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Kahlifa
Fahima, denied placing a bomb in Malta in a suitcase that later
was transferred onto the Pan Am Flight 103 in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The defense counsel, who launched a special defense on the
first day of the trial by blaming two Palestinian groups and
individuals, questioned the police officer about the kind of the
bomb detonator that might have been used.
</P>
<P>
The police officer was also questioned about Palestinian
attacks on Israeli airliners in the early 1970s by using
barometric trigger that caused mid-air bombing after reaching
certain altitudes.
</P>
<P>
A three-year investigation immediately after the tragedy led to
the issuance in 1991 of an arrest warrant for al-Megrahi and
Fahima.
</P>
<P>
In August 1998, the United States and Britain accepted a Libyan
offer of a trial in the Netherlands under the Scots Law and the
two accused Libyans surrendered themselves to the Dutch police in
April 1999.
</P>
<P>
The trial is expected to last at least one year and is
estimated to cost some 3 million U.S. dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
Court officials said that the court would hold sessions almost
daily through July 28 before adjourning until August 22.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
