<HEADLINE> Salvage Begins for Foreign Ships' Collision in Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 5 (Xinhua) -- China sent its largest water rescue
crane to the lower reaches of the Yangtze River today to salvage
the Cambodian ship "Conan" which sank after a collision Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Conan was bound for Nanjing, in east China's Jiangsu
Province, from Mokpo of the Republic of Korea, carrying over 10,
000 tons of rolled steel. It collided with Panamanian cargo-free
ship "Robin Forest" at about 18:35 (Beijing time) in the waters of
Nantong at the lower Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
The captain of the Conan ordered his crew to abandon the
sinking ship at 23:50. By early Thursday morning, the deck was
almost fully submerged.
</P>
<P>
Other equipment and tugboats have also been sent to the site
for rescue work.
</P>
<P>
No injuries or deaths of those on board either ship were
reported. 
</P>
