<HEADLINE> Charity Leaders Call for Building Sustainable Communities (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Business, government and non-
governmental sectors must join hands to explore diversified
resources to build sustainable communities, delegates to an
international charity conference here have said.
</P>
<P>
The "United Way International (UWI) World Assembly 2000" is
being held from May 4 to 6 for leaders from corporations,
foundations, international non-government organizations to explore
new and innovative ways to meet the welfare needs of the
communities.
</P>
<P>
The assembly "provides an opportunity to share experiences and
information and to explore ideas in enhancing fund-raising
initiatives," said Chief Executive of Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region Tung Chee Hwa while addressing the opening
ceremony on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
To explore new and innovative fund-raising initiatives, panel
discussions were held for representatives from UWI affiliates to
introduce in details their charitable practices and volunteer
programs.
</P>
<P>
These discussions are enlightening, said president of China
Charity Federation Yan Mingfu, who believes China's fund-raisers
can learn from their western counterparts in many respects.
</P>
<P>
"Charities in western countries have a long history of hundreds
of years, and as a result, in legal protection, institutional
maturity and their volunteer program, they have done a better job
than us." said Yan, also head of the Chinese delegation to the
conference.
</P>
<P>
Noting that some western countries' taxing system encourages
donations, Yan cited the specific provisions on levying of
donations in some countries, where people can be 100 percent tax-
free when donating a heritage to a charitable organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charity Leaders Call for Building Sustainable Communities (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese charitable organizations have things to do in raising
the society's awareness of charity and partnering with government
and non-government sectors to create sustainable communities, Yan
said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong people were praised by Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
for their generosity in supporting relief efforts in all parts of
the world, and by UWI Chairman Arthur P. Bellis for their "long
tradition of caring for those in need."
</P>
<P>
Darwin Chen, chief executive of the Community Chest of Hong
Kong which finances 140 Hong Kong charitable agencies, believed
all sectors of a society should join force in building harmonious
and sustainable communities, stressing that welfare of communities
requires support from the public as well as the government.
</P>
<P>
Charity concerns two aspects, Chen said. One is to provide
necessary service, including supporting the old, orphans and the
disabled, the other is to improve service quality and find
resources to support such kind of service, he elaborated.
</P>
<P>
Chen praised the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
government for its increasing support to charitable causes and
also called for people's support in helping build a caring society.
</P>
<P>
The UWI was established in 1974. Headquartered in Virginia, U.S.
, the organization now has affiliates in 35 countries and regions,
including the Community Chest in Hong Kong and China Charity
Foundation on the mainland.  
</P>
