<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The Moroccan Supreme Council for Planning and Economic
Recovery on Thursday approved the 2000-2004 Five Year Plan, which
targets at a 5.5 percent economic growth rate.
</P>
<P>
The 140-billion-dirham (13.8 billion U.S. dollars) plan, the 8th
in Morocco since 1956, expects a kick-start growth rate of 3
percent this year due to the current dry season in the country.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- Qatar is taking steps toward a return to the
international bonds market in few weeks to raise about 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars from 30-year maturity treasury bonds, thus becoming
the second Gulf country into the field.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The current economic stagnation in Egypt would come to
an end with the start of the coming fiscal year in July, said
Egyptian Finance Minister Mohamed Medhat Hassaneen on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Besides injecting funds, the Egyptian government has adopted
some measures to cope with the stagnation, including credit policy
revision, interest rates reduction, psychologically qualifying
market dealers and promotion of available liquidity, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni-EU Joint Commission concluded its 9th
session in Sanaa on Wednesday stressing the need to "establish EU-
funded businesses in Yemen and encourage Yemen's farm exports to
the 15-nation bloc."
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued at the conclusion of the meetings,
the two sides agreed on speeding up the endorsement of the Pact on
Supporting Free Trade Zones Authority with 1.8 million euros (1.6
million U.S. dollars) and funding the structural reforms at the
ministries of health, social affairs and insurance, and civil
aviation in Yemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
