<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli North Hit By Guerrilla Rockets For Second Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Katyusha rockets fired by Lebanese
Hezbollah guerrillas Friday struck Galilee Panhandle and other
Israeli northern areas for a second straight day, wounding several
persons, damaging properties and triggering fire.
</P>
<P>
Four waves of rockets landed in the areas, where local residents
just emerged from a night in their bomb shelters and went to market
for the weekend, according to Israel Radio reports.
</P>
<P>
They had been ordered by Israel Defense Forces (IDF) to lock
themselves into shelters overnight after the Hezbollah's Katyusha
attacks against the same areas Thursday afternoon, the fiercest
offensive in more than a year, killed an IDF soldier and wounded 28
civilians.
</P>
<P>
However, the shopping crowd was scattered back to their
underground havens immediately after hearing the rocket blasts on
Friday morning. They were advised to continue staying there until
further notice.
</P>
<P>
To prevent possible food shortage, the army distributed food in
the north for the Jewish Shabbat.
</P>
<P>
Senior military analysts pointed out that the accurate launching
of these Katyusha rockets was undoubtedly intended to kill as many
persons as possible and not just as a scare tactic.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah, who have been fighting against Israeli occupation
in the so-called security zone in south Lebanon for decades,
claimed responsibility for Friday's attacks, saying that the
rockets are the answer for Israel's overnight air raids against
Lebanon infrastructure targets.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Air Force (IAF) attacks, which Israel claimed were in
turn the reprisal for Thursday's Katyusha rockets fired by
Hezbollah, blasted power transformers in Lebanon early Friday,
cutting off power supply for large areas.
</P>
<P>
It also targeted guerrilla strongholds and severed the Beirut-
Damascus highway.
</P>
<P>
Although the international community is calling on both sides to
refrain from attacking civilians, the cries for further retaliation
against Hezbollah are currently loud from Israeli political
echelons.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who toured the northern areas
Thursday night, stressed that no country in the world will tolerate
bombardment of its population center by Katyusha rockets, and
Israel will not let these "terrorist attacks" pass without
punishment.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh warned that if Hezbollah
continued cross-border rocket firing, the IDF's response will be
upgraded to a new level.
</P>
<P>
Ariel Sharon, leader of the opposition Likud party, said at a
party meeting on Friday that the IDF must act decisively to send
Lebanon and Syria, the major power broker in Lebanon, a serious
message that "they must fight terrorism directed at Israel."
</P>
<P>
Even President Ezer Weizman, a traditional dovish figure, said
Friday morning that Israel will "darken Lebanon's world" if the
Hezbollah attacks continue.
</P>
<P>
The president, a former IAF Commander, also praised the IDF's
accuracy in reprisal raids against Lebanese infrastructure sites
overnight, while he was visiting Kiryat Shemona, the border town
having been the major target of Hezbollah attacks.
</P>
<P>
It is still not clear if the escalating situation will affect
the scheduled July pullback by Israeli army from the buffer zone,
which was set up by Israel in 1985 with a self-claimed aim to
protect its north from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
On March 5, Israeli cabinet approved a withdrawal from the zone
by July, but with a warning that Israel will not hesitate to
revenge if any militant groups test its strains on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
