<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt. Assessing MILF Move on Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said Friday that his government is now studying the move by the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) to declare a 48-hour
unilateral ceasefire in Mindanao effective Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing at the Presidential Palace, the president
expressed the hope that this would pave the way for the resumption
of formal peace negotiations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"We are aware of the declaration by the MILF of a 48-hour
unilateral ceasefire in Mindanao effective 6 a.m. tomorrow," said
the president.
</P>
<P>
"The government is assessing this MILF move, which we hope
will clear the way for the return of the government and the MILF
peace panels to the negotiating table," he added.
</P>
<P>
Estrada stressed that his government remains committed to
extend the hand of peace to those who seek it, but is also
determined to defeat those who choose war.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that despite the clamor for peace by an
overwhelming majority of the people, MILF elements and Abu Sayyaf
extremists have launched attacks against government troops and
engaged in criminal acts that have claimed the lives of military
combatants and innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
"These MILF and Abu Sayyaf elements have openly challenged the
Republic. We have responded, and will continue to respond, to
their criminal acts in the swiftest, most appropriate manner," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the integrity of the Philippines is non-
negotiable and the government will fight against all form of
terrorism, torture, murder and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he admitted that the roots of the Mindanao conflict
are deep and complex, which "can be resolved only by a
comprehensive, political economic, social, cultural and even
ecological approach."
</P>
<P>
Philippine government troops have engaged in battles with two
rebel groups, the MILF and the Abu Sayyaf, in the last few days in
Mindanao. About 20 government soldiers and more than 100 rebels
were killed in the battles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
