<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Africa to Continue Quiet Diplomacy Towards Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Yu Dabo
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki headed for Zimbabwe on Friday amid mounting domestic demand
for tougher reaction and growing international concern over the
situation in that country.
</P>
<P>
He will meet his Zimbabwean counterpart Robert Mugabe to sort
things out in a "quiet diplomacy" which will go far beyond the
expectations of various political parties at home. His visit,
therefore, would be unlikely to produce what the opposition
parties had expected.
</P>
<P>
In a televised speech to the nation on Thursday, Mbeki defended
his government's quiet diplomacy over the crisis in Zimbabwe,
saying South Africa would "work consistently and without making
the noise of empty drums to help the sister people of Zimbabwe to
find a just and lasting solution to the real and pressing land
question in that country."
</P>
<P>
His address followed increasingly strident calls from
opposition parties and international elements for Pretoria to take
a tougher line with Zimbabwean President Mugabe over land
invasions and the collapse of the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki has endured criticism for refusing to openly condemn
Mugabe's support of farm invasions and for failing to come up with
South African initiatives to solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's farm invasions have set off fears among South
African commercial farmers that the same invasions could happen to
them. In a move to quell such fears, Mbeki pledged that South
Africa would not slide into a similar land crisis.
</P>
<P>
But his address failed to ease criticism at home. Opposition
parties lambasted his address as an ineffectual apologia which did
nothing to address the crisis of human and political rights in
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean crisis has helped push the rand, currency of
South Africa, to a new low against the U.S. dollar on Thursday,
bringing more pressure on Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said one major reason for the South African
government to insist on a "soft approach" towards the Zimbabwean
land crisis was that Pretoria has similar land problems and too
much reaction would put the government in an awkward situation.
</P>
<P>
There have been urgent calls for land reforms in South Africa
where the minority whites own most of the farm lands and the
majority of blacks are landless. "If the government reacted too
strongly to Zimbabwe's land crisis, it might make the black
majority in South Africa unhappy," said a diplomatic source asking
for anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The South African government, which wanted a smooth and
peaceful land reform, apparently objected the radical move by the
Zimbabwean war veterans to seize land. But in this subtle
situation, it had to seek a balanced approach and the quiet
diplomacy was the best choice, the diplomatic source said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki has made it clear that the land dispossession of the
indigenous black majority in Zimbabwe was a colonial legacy which,
first of all, needs to be addressed by both Zimbabwe and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Out of this consideration, South Africa has time and again
called on Britain to help solve the crisis. South Africa could
offer help but did not want to spearhead the campaign, according
to a government source.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean situation was different from that of Mozambique
earlier this year when South Africa sent troops to the country to
help fighting the flood, the same source said.
</P>
<P>
However, the quiet diplomacy pursued by the South African
government was not a passive or apathetic one, the source
stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, South Africa was ready to work
together with the British and Zimbabwean governments to achieve a
common commitment to end violence and create conditions for the
withdrawal of demonstrating war veterans from the farms they had
occupied.
</P>
<P>
"Quiet diplomacy does not mean silence," the source noted.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to wipe out scepticism, Mbeki said he had not been
silent on the issue, contrary to press reports which failed to
cover all that he had said.
</P>
<P>
The president warned that there were racist attempts to create
an atmosphere of fear in South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
