<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Warns of Love Bug Virus Mutants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on Friday
warned that "love bug" computer virus mutants might appear in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, said that less than 1 percent of the institution's
computers were affected by the virus that was first detected
toward midday on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It was a serious attack," said one commission spokesman, who
added that the commission immediately gave warnings to internal
computer users.
</P>
<P>
The software suppliers of the commission soon provided the
European institution with anti-virus programs.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman warned that variant virus was expected to
enter the commission in the coming days though no virus mutant had
been spotted so far.
</P>
<P>
When asked, the spokesman said that the commission was not in a
position to confirm that the "love bug" computer virus had
originated from the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Computer security experts here said that the "love bug" virus
has infected millions of computers in the world and is likely to
spawn more versions and linger for a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
The fast-spreading computer virus was believed to have
originated from two Philippine E-mail addresses. The virus first
hit companies in Taiwan and Hong Kong before spreading further to
Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The original virus appears in an E-mail as "ILOVEYOU", enticing
users to open the letter, which will do damage to the user's mail
system. One of the virus' variant uses the word "Joke" in the
subject line of the document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
