<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks to Review Strategies to Stay Competitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- China's entry to the World Trade
Organization could force large domestic Chinese banks to consider
seeking capital from sources other than the state in order to
effectively counter foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
This could push banks toward Initial Public Offerings (IPOs)
and tapping the international capital markets, said Credit Suisse
First Boston (CSFB) in a report released Friday in Hong Kong on
China's financial sector reform.
</P>
<P>
John Hobson, CSFB's director and head of the Asian Banking
Research, pointed out in the report that the successful listing of
the Chinese banks will be dependent upon factors including
corporate governance and disclosure, legal and regulatory
framework, operational efficiency, technology and most importantly,
credit quality.
</P>
<P>
"The four largest state-owned banks, Agricultural Bank of China,
Bank of China, China Construction Bank and Industrial and
Commercial Bank of China, control approximately 70 percent of the
banking system including problem assets," said Hobson.
</P>
<P>
The four asset management companies set up by the four banks
had already taken on problem loans totaling 350 billion yuan (39.5
billion U.S. dollars) by late 1999 and a total of 1 trillion yuan
(121.95 billion U.S. dollars) is expected to be carved out from
the banking system soon. This will undoubtedly help improve the
asset quality of the state-owned banks and is an important step
forward.
</P>
<P>
China entry to the WTO will allow foreign integrated financial
groups access to the market.
</P>
<P>
"To compete going forward, we believe Chinese financial
services supermarkets will need to emerge. In our view, the
regulatory framework will also need to adapt further and possibly
a super-regulator will emerge as has occurred in some other
markets," added Hobson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Reports Red Tide Sightings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- An inter-departmental red tide
working group announced on Friday that they found four red tide
sightings within Hong Kong waters, keeping the public well
informed of the latest monitoring situation.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the working group said a red tide formed by
Prorocentrum sigmoides was observed at Kat O Fisheries Substation
of the Agriculture, Fisheries and Conservation Department on April
29 but it had dissipated the next day.
</P>
<P>
On May 3 and 4, the staff of the department also reported other
three red tide sightings, still persisting in the sea areas.
</P>
<P>
All red tide species identified are non-toxic, the spokesman
said. "They have been sighted in Hong Kong waters before but led
to no associated fish kill," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that red tides formed by these species could
have a potential to affect cultured fish through oxygen depletion.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said red tide was a natural phenomenon and the
department's pro-active and comprehensive phytoplankton monitoring
program would continue monitoring red tide occurrence to minimize
its impact on the mariculture industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM to Meet Annan on Withdrawal from S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
will travel to New York next week for a meeting with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to discuss issues concerning Israel's
planned pullout from south Lebanon by July, Israel Radio reported
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting comes at a time when the northern border of Israel
is witnessing an escalation of conflicts beween Hezbollah
guerrillas and Israeli forces, which have inflicted casualties on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, U.N. Middle East special envoy Terje Larsen is
paying a three-day visit to Lebanon starting on Wednesday to
discuss Israel's proposed withdrawal from south Lebanon and the
future of the international peacekeepers deployed there for the
past 22 years.
</P>
<P>
Larsen, who held talks with Israeli officials on the pullout
last week, told reporters that the United Nations is looking
forward to implementing Resolutions 425 and 426, which demand a
full Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon as well as the return of
the Lebanese government's authority over the area.
</P>
<P>
The U.N envoy held talks with Lebanese President Emile Lahoud
and Prime Minister Salim Hoss on the pullout, which Israel said
will be completed by July 7. Hoss told Larsen that Israel's
withdrawal should include the release of all Lebanese prisoners and
the return of all occupied land, including Shabaa Farms, a disputed
area that edges the Golan Heights and was once held by Syria.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, three key Arab foreign ministers, Faruk Shareh of
Syria, Amr Moussa of Egypt and Saudi Arabia's Prince Saud al-
Faisal, voiced their support for the United Nations to take control
of security in south Lebanon following Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers, winding up talks in the Syrian city of
Palmyra, 240 kilometers northeast of Damascus, said in a statement
that the United Nations should shoulder its responsibilities in
accordance with the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL),
established in 1978 in line with Resolution 425 from nine
countries, was primarily deployed in the western and central
sectors of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In the event of a complete pullout of the Israel Defense Forces
(IDF), it is expected that the U.N. peace force will be required to
be deployed to the international border, which will necessitate the
expansion of the force.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which for years has evaded U.S. and international calls
for contributing IDF personnel to U.N. forces, is considering the
issue of repaying the U.N. forces for filling up the void left in
south Lebanon as a result of its pullout and "sponsoring" the
pullout itself, the Israeli daily Ha'artz reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided in March to pull back its forces in south Lebanon
with or without a peace deal with Syria, the main power broker in
Lebanon. It has also formally notified the United Nations of its
withdrawal determination.
</P>
<P>
But Beirut has warned Israel of more frontier violence if it
quits Lebanon without a peace accord with Syria, which backs the
Hezbollah guerrillas fighting in the south.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh said Wednesday that there
is still chance of establishing peace with Israel. He told
reporters after talks with his Egyptian and Saudi counterparts
that "contacts in this regard did not stop."
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Russia is reportedly launching a new Middle
East peace initiative to bring the deadlocked Israeli-Syrian talks
back on track. Russia's Mideast special envoy Nicolai Kartuzov, who
is now visiting Israel, said on Wednesday that his country would
like to send a special envoy to Syria to help restart its talks
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Larsen is scheduled to head to Damascus on Saturday to continue
his "fact-finding tour" in the Middle East region. He will also
meet UNIFIL officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Malaysia Achieves in Betterment of Rural Life (by Wu Dingbao) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 5 (Xinhua) -- After having made efforts for
decades, Malaysia has achieved tremendously in improving the rural
life, Rural Development Minister Azmi Khalid said.
</P>
<P>
In peninsular Malaysia, 98 percent of villages now have metal
roads of 6-foot wide suitable for one car passing and the villages
are linked with 40-foot wide rural roads to highways, the minister
told Xinhua in a recent exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
Again in peninsular Malaysia, 98 percent of rural areas where
45 percent of the country's some 22 million population are living
have tap water and electricity, he said.
</P>
<P>
And 90 percent of villages in Malaysia have telephone
facilities, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that to Malaysia, rural development is a
political and national agenda to enable the rural people to be
active economically and to ensure political stability in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The responsibility of bettering the rural life is not only with
the Rural Development Ministry, but with the whole government,
because historically, regions away from cities were occupied by
Malays who formed the political base in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
"So UMNO (United Malays National Organization), the backbone of
the government, made it a national policy to develop rural areas,"
the minister said, adding "Strategically, we started with basic
infrastructure including building roads joining village to village
and house to house, providing water for irrigation and drinking,
and electricity and telecommunication facilities."
</P>
<P>
Azmi said that the government spent a lot on rural development.
For example, he said that for the last five years (1996-2000), the
government allocated 3.4 billion ringgit (894.736 million U.S.
dollars), among which 1.4 billion ringgit (368.421 million dollars)
for village and rural roads construction, 1.27 billion ringgit (
334.21 million dollars) for water supply, and the rest amount for
other purposes.
</P>
<P>
He said that for the next five years (2001-2005), his ministry
is asking for 5 billion ringgit (1.315 billion dollars) for rural
development mainly in the areas of roads construction, water and
electricity supply, rural industry, rural education for pre-school
kids, and human resources development and religious education.
</P>
<P>
All these basic amenities are planned to create an environment
where the people can be active economically.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, the government pays great attention to
education in rural areas by setting up schools and providing
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
"For students from remote areas, we have hostels for them to
stay. There are many residential schools in rural areas throughout
Malaysia," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Education is the main part on which the government has really
spent money," he added.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the minister said that by now, only 6.8 percent of
the country's population are poor in comparison with that more
than half of its population were poor when Malaysia became
independent in 1957. "We are targeting that by the year 2005, we
want to eradicate the poverty."
</P>
<P>
"Now the Malaysian society is peaceful with different races
living together, respecting each other.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia is a multi-racial country. For that, we must continue
to have peace, so we must make sure that people are economically
active, living comfortably, we do not allow that one race is rich
and another poor, so that we can enjoy political stability and
continuous economic growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our vision is that the rural areas are developed to be
attractive places with very good environment and all necessary
facilities and economically viable and to be decent places to
bring up families, and are linked up by roads and highways with
any other parts of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"By the year 2020 when Malaysia achieves its vision of becoming
a developed nation, 74 percent of our population will be living in
urban areas because by then towns become bigger and rural areas
now will be no more rural," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the challenge to Malaysia is to make
sure that the population growth (at an annual rate of 2.5 percent)
does not spoil the environment. For that, he said, the government
enacted laws for environment protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
