<HEADLINE> U.N. Warns S. Leone Rebels of Facing Possible Prosecution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the United Nations
peace- keeping mission in S. Leone (UNAMSIL) has warned the
country's former rebel leaders of possible prosecution of their
holding U.N. personnel hostage and killing of its soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here Friday morning from Freetown quoted
spokesman Philip Winslow as saying in the West African capital
that an amnesty granted to rebels under last year's Lome peace
accord did not cover acts.
</P>
<P>
"Those responsible will definitely be prosecuted," he said at a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
In another latest development, the U.N. officials in New York
on Thursday had revised the death toll among peacekeepers down
from seven to four. They said that no bodies had been recovered
yet.
</P>
<P>
They put the number of UNAMSIL peacekeepers and civilians staff
being held in Makeni and Kailahun in the east of the country at
69, up from 49 previously, but said that the total could be even
higher.
</P>
<P>
The UNAMSIL spokesman in Sierra Leone also warned on Thursday
that the recent attacks on U.N. troops by rebels could lead to
violent confrontations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
He accused the rebels of the Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
of completely destroying disarmament camps in the country's
central towns of Makeni and Magburaka, in addition to taking
dozens of U.N. personnel hostage and killing of its soldiers.
</P>
</TEXT>
