<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Livingstone Officially Declared London Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Ken Livingstone, the independent
candidate and maverick MP expelled from Labor, was officially
declared as London's first directly elected mayor on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Livingstone won the poll despite a late surge in support for
Tory Steve Norris - with Labor's Frank Dobson trailing well behind
on a disastrous election night for Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
Livingstone, who stood as an independent after being rejected
by the ruling Labor party, won easily in a low turnout, according
to the official results of Thursday's vote.
</P>
<P>
Only a third of London's five million voters cast their ballots.
But the left-winger's victory hurt Prime Minister Tony Blair's
Labor party, whose hand-picked candidate Frank Dobson was pummeled
into an embarrassing third place.
</P>
<P>
Livingstone won the vote after second preferences were
calculated during a marathon election count.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere across England, Labor lost control of 14 local
councils as the Tories and Liberal Democrats gained ground. But
there was a surprise as the Conservatives lost to the Liberal
Democrats in the Romsey by-election.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair said he would be speaking to
Livingstone following his victory -- but said his views about
London's new mayor had not changed.
</P>
<P>
He said: "It is important that we do what we can as a
government to make sure that this works for London and works for
Londoners. We accept our responsibility in that regard."
</P>
<P>
But Blair made it clear Livingstone would not be allowed to
return to Labor after standing against an official party candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
