<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks closed the week
slightly lower in thin trade on Friday, as investors became
cautious ahead of the release of the U.S. unemployment data.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's property giant Cheung Kong (Holdings) Ltd and
Hutchison Whampoa, owned by tycoon Li Ka-shing, put pressure over
the stock market as they face the possible downgrades by the
credit agencies.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index fell slightly 45.43 points, or 0.30 percent,
to finish the week at 15,268.64 Friday, with the turnover only of
7.174 billion HK dollars (919 million U.S. dollars), the lowest
level in the past six months.
</P>
<P>
Of the four sub-indices, Utilities and Commerce and Industry
rose 1.23 percent and 0.11 percent respectively, while Finance and
Properties fell 0.64 percent and 1.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
China-related index ended mixed with the Hang Seng China
Enterprises Index down 0.09 percent and the Hang Seng China-
Affiliated Corp Index up 0.21 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng IT Index shed 0.05 percent and the Hang Seng IT
Portfolio Index edged up 0.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared to the last Friday close, the blue chips fell 250.66
points or 1.62 percent this week. 
</P>
