<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank on Baht Depreciation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand (BOT), claimed
Friday that it will not interfere with the recent tumbling of the
Thai baht, saying that the depreciation was caused by outside
factors.
</P>
<P>
Therachai Puvanathnaranuban, BOT Assistant Governor said in an
statement that as both Thailand's foreign equity markets and
exchange trading volume remain normal, BOT has no plan to
intervene, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
"However, BOT will continue to monitor the situation closely,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Therachai said the weakening of the Thai currency is largely
due to investors' expectation that the United States would raise
its interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Thursday afternoon, the baht tumbled to between 38.52 and 38.00,
to the dollar down from 38.35 to 38 to the dollar in the morning
trading. 
</P>
