<HEADLINE> India to Consider Humanitarian Aid to Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh told reporters that
humanitarian assistance to Colombo "could be considered if and
when sought but the situation has not arisen yet."
</P>
<P>
"There is no question of going down the International Peace
Keeping Force route of 1978. The question of Indian military
intervention in Sri Lanka simply does not arise," he added.
</P>
<P>
Singh's remarks came after an hour-long meeting Prime Minister
Atal Bihari Vajpayee had with Tamil Nadu Chief Minister M.
Karunanidhi.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil Nadu chief minister, who flew here last night
following a request by the Indian prime minister, held
consultations with the central government on the evolving
situation in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by Home Minister L. K. Advani,
Defense Minister George Fernandes and Commerce Minister Muraasoli
Maran. 
</P>
