<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Build 100,000 Model Rural Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is planning to
 transform 100,000 rural settlements in the country into rural
model communities in a bid to uplift the living standard of rural
dwellers.
</P>
<P>
This Day, a leading Nigerian newspaper, Friday quoted Minister
of Information Jerry Gana as saying that the plan was a clear
indication of the high premium the government attached to the
development of the country' s rural communities as an instrument
for achieving sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the media in the capital Abuja Thursday, Gana said
that every year 1,000 communities in each of the country's six
geo-political zones would be targeted for transformation.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the model communities, when eventually on
board, would be equipped with adequate infrastructural facilities
and support services.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the plan would enhance productivity and
income- generating activities to stimulate rural economic growth
and development, said the minister, adding that all federal
ministries would have their activities properly harmonized and
coordinated for better results during the process.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the determination of the government to
pursue its national food security program, saying the food
security scheme was designed to store food stocks against times of
emergency and to facilitate price stabilization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
