<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Livingstone Heads for Victory in London Mayoral Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Ken Livingstone, the independent
candidate and maverick MP expelled from Labour, is heading for the
political history books as London's first elected mayor, according
to initial results released Friday.
</P>
<P>
Livingstone is set to triumph in the poll despite a late surge
in support for Conservative candidate Steve Norris.
</P>
<P>
Frank Dobson, the Labour candidate who beat Livingstone in the
party's bitter selection battle, was trailing on 13 percent, a
major blow to party leaders who had been determined to stop
Livingstone.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere across England, Labour lost control of 14 local
councils as the Tories and Liberal Democrats gained ground.
</P>
<P>
In the elections for the 14 Greater London Assembly (GLA)
constituency seats, the Tories won eight to Labour's six, with the
BBC predicting that the parties will each take nine seats in the
25-member assembly when the "top-up" results are calculated.
</P>
<P>
The GLA results showed Livingstone clearly in front with 41
percent of first preference votes, indicating that he would win
the mayoralty with the help of second preference votes.
</P>
<P>
Despite a low turnout, the final mayoral result is not expected
until 1100 GMT on Friday after problems with counting equipment.
</P>
<P>
Norris polled 26 percent of first preference votes in the first
GLA seats to declare, while Liberal Democrat Susan Kramer is
battling for third place with Dobson on 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
In English council elections, Labour lost control of Bradford,
Hartlepool, Oxford and Portsmouth, with Tory gains in Cherwell,
Eastbourne, Solihull -- a major target for the party -- and Torbay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
