<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Grabs Three Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
TOKYO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan, led by Miya Tachibana, took
three gold medals in the solo, duet and team events Friday at the
Japan Open synchronized swimming championships.
</P>
<P>
Tachibana, member of world silver medalists and the bronze
medallist at the 1998 world championships, regained the solo
trophy she won three straight times from 1995, beating 1997 world
junior silver medallist Jang Yoon-Kyeong of South Korea, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Tachibana then took her eighth straight team title with seven
other swimmers using a programme for the Sydney Olympic Games
beating France into second.
</P>
<P>
Tachibana, five-time former duet champion here, added the duet
crown for the first time with Miho Takeda, underlining their
status as the world silver medallist pair.
</P>
<P>
Second place came to Canadians Claire Carver-Dias and Fanny
Letourneau while Chinese pair Li Min and Li Yuanyuan were third.
</P>
<P>
Tachibana and Takeda earned four 9.8s and a 9.9 for technical
merit and three 9.9s and two 9.8s for artistic impression in
Friday's free routine for a combined 98.174 points.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese team also gained three 9.8s and two 9.9s for
technical merit and five 9.9s for the artistic impression for a
combined 98.437.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
