</P>
<P>
-- The interior ministers of Egypt, Jordan and Saudi Arabia have
called on Arab countries to ratify the Arab anti-terrorism
agreement. Saudi Interior Minister Nayef Bin Abdul-Aziz said it
takes ratification by all parties to fully implement the agreement,
while his Jordanian counterpart Nayef al-Kadi stressed security
cooperation and coordination among Arab countries in light of the
agreement that aims at realizing stability for all Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Al Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- France, Italy and Japan have voiced readiness to help Egypt
launch a remote-sensing satellite to be used in desert development
projects. The satellite would also serve regions bordering Egypt in
Africa, the Arab region and the Gulf region in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- Three key Arab foreign ministers said Thursday they wanted
the United Nations to take control of security in south Lebanon
following Israel's planned withdrawal from the area. It was the
first time that the three, Faruk Shareh of Syria, Amr Moussa of
Egypt and Saudi Arabia's Prince Saud al-Faisal, had voiced support
for such a U.N. role. 
