<HEADLINE> Estrada Enraged Over Slain Hostages' Torture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
has expressed outrage over the torture of four civilian hostages
who were later executed by the extremist group Abu Sayyaf in the
southern Basilan province.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said Friday the president
was also deeply saddened after receiving reports of the torture of
the victims from the Cabinet Cluster E.
</P>
<P>
"The president was angered and saddened by this report. It was
clear that the victims were tortured severely and later killed by
the Abu Sayyaf," Zamora said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the government's assurance to the victims'
families that they will get justice for their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
The four tortured hostages included a priest and three teachers.
"We will finish this. We hope for the recovery of the remaining
hostages," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
Citing reports reaching the Cabinet Cluster E, which handles
political affairs and national security concerns, Zamora said the
four victims were tortured before being slain, and not killed in a
crossfire as the extremists claimed.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the four victims were recovered on Wednesday by
the military along with 15 hostages abducted by the Abu Sayyaf on
March 20. About 10 other hostages taken by the extremist group are
still unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
Zamora added that the government is now verifying reports that
Abu Sayyaf leader Khadafy Janjalani and spokesman Abu Sayyaf were
killed in Wednesday's encounter with the military in Basilan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
