<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "LoveLetter" Virus Infection Confirmed in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Infocomm Development Authority
(IDA) of Singapore Friday confirmed the spreading in Singapore of
the new computer virus dubbed "LoveLetter" and issued a media
alert to advise PC users of necessary precautions to protect
themselves against potential virus attacks.
</P>
<P>
In a press release released Friday afternoon, IDA said, "
Instances of the 'LoveLetter' virus spreading in Singapore have
been reported to SingCERT (Singapore Computer Emergency Response
Team)." SingCERT is a joint operation unit set up by the IDA and
the National University of Singapore to assist companies in
handling computer incidents such as computer hacking and viruses.
</P>
<P>
Without giving any detail of these instances, IDA only said
that the Sysmantec AntiVirus Research Center began receiving
reports regarding this worm in the early hours of May 4, 2000, and
the worm appeared to have originated from Manila in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
According to IDA, the worm has been known to arrive in an e-
mail message with its subject in the form of "ILOVEYOU." When
activated, it sends itself to e-mail addresses in the Microsoft
Outlook address book and spreads itself via micro and infects
files on local and remote drives.
</P>
<P>
Quoting unnamed anti-virus experts, IDA strongly advised
infected PC users to refrain from using the infected computer on
account that the virus replicates itself many times within the
infected computer.
</P>
<P>
It also advised PC users to take necessary precautions to
protect against virus attacks in general and to regularly observe
seven items of precautionary practices such as the installing and
updating of anti-virus software, exercising caution in reading e-
mails from unknown sources, making regular back-ups of important
data files. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
