<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Proposed Investment Projects Drop in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Approved investment projects in
Cambodia in the first three months of this year fell to 31.6
million U.S. dollars from 120 million dollars in the same period
last year, the Cambodia Daily reported Friday, quoting figures of
the government.
</P>
<P>
Only 23 proposed projects were approved in the first quarter,
compared with 32 proposed projects in the same period in 1999,
according to the Council for the Development of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The totals for the first quarter also were down dramatically
from fourth quarter 1999 with 31 pledged projects worth 239.4
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the decline to lingering negative image and
the slow recovery in Asia financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Another reason may be the government's new investment policy
which requires investors to deposit up to 2 percent of its project
's capital amount into a performance bond.
</P>
<P>
According to the development council data, there are no tourism
investment projects approved in the first quarter. Almost all of
the investments approved in the first quarter were for
manufacturing industries such as textiles and machine assembly
while garment manufacturing accounted for 12 projects with 18.7
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
This year's figures also show that nearly 60 percent of the
investments were made by investors from the Asia-Pacific region
excluding ASEAN members which accounted for only 7.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
