<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Fires Katyushas on Northern Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Hezbollah guerrillas Friday morning
fired several Katyusha rockets into northern Israel, following
Israeli air raids on Lebanon overnight, Sound of People Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Israeli military sources have confirmed the rocket attacks, but
did not disclose any casualties, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hezbollah said in a statement that it had fired on "
the Zionist settlements of Shlomi and Kiryat Shmona in reprisal for
repeated Israeli aggressions against Lebanese civilians."
</P>
<P>
It also warned Israel against continuing these attacks on
Lebanon
and vowed to respond to such attacks.
</P>
<P>
On the wee hours of Friday, Israeli war planes bombed two power
stations in Tripoli and Beirut in retaliation for Hezbollah's
Katyusha rocket attacks on northern Israel late Thursday, during
which one Israeli solider was killed and several civilians injured.
</P>
<P>
Israel has occupied parts of south Lebanon since 1978. It set up
a 15-kilometer-deep security zone there in 1982 with a claimed aim
of protecting its northern settlements from cross-border guerrilla
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Hezbollah, or Party of God, with the backing of Iran
and Syria, has been spearheading a guerrilla war to oust Israeli
forces and their proxy militia South Lebanon Army from the country.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Israel formally informed the United Nations of its
decision to withdraw from south Lebanon by July in implementation
of the U.N. Resolutions 425 and 426, with or without a peace
agreement with Lebanon and its major power broker Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
