<HEADLINE> Cyprus Names New Commander of National Guard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Lieutenant General Evangelos Florakis
has been appointed as new commander of Cyprus' National Guard, the
Cyprus Weekly newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The appointment is to be subjected to approval by the Council of
Ministers.
</P>
<P>
Florakis, a retired military man, will replace Lieutenant
General Dimitris Demou, whose term of office ended last week.
</P>
<P>
Florakis, born in Arta, Greece, in 1943, has served in Cyprus on
two previous occasions.
</P>
<P>
He started his military career as a Cadet in 1962 and while he
climbed up the brass ladder, he graduated from various other
military schools, including the Parachuting Academy in Greece.
</P>
<P>
His last post in Greece, as recent as 1999-2000, was the
commander of the 2nd Army Corp.
</P>
<P>
The National Guard, the Cyprus Republic's armed forces, consists
of some 20,000 servicemen commanded by a Greek mainlander, plus a
reserve force of 100,000.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus also has a 2,000-strong Greek contingent, which provides
for training for the army of the Republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island after a
failed coup in Nicosia seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The number of the Turkish Cypriot security forces in northern
Cyprus is put at 4,500 commanded by a Turkish mainlander, in
addition to 35,000 heavily armed Turkish soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
