<HEADLINE> Philippine Inflation Up Slightly to 3.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' year-on-year
inflation rose slightly to 3.7 percent in April from 3.3 percent
in March due to higher prices of services, housing and repairs,
and petroleum products, the National Statistics Office said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The April inflation figure, the highest so far this year, was a
significant improvement from the 7.9 percent inflation registered
in the same month in 1999, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate for Metro Manila increased to 3.4 percent in
April from 3.2 percent in March. On the other hand, inflation in
areas outside Metro Manila went up to 3.8 percent in April from 3.
4 percent a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation rate averaged 6.6 percent in 1999,
better than the government target of 7 percent to 8 percent. The
Philippine government has set an inflation target of 5 percent to
6 percent for 2000, a goal most analysts believe is achievable.
</P>
</TEXT>
