<HEADLINE> Manila to Keep Military Cordon in Sulu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The military cordon in Sulu
surrounding the area where the kidnappers of the 21 tourists have
holed up will remain in place, the Philippine government
maintained Friday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in a radio interview
that the government will put a premium on the hostages' safety,
but will not allow their kidnappers to escape.
</P>
<P>
"Our policy in his situation is containment in response to the
request of foreign governments. We don't want to assault the area
where the hostages, now divided into five groups, are being held,
but we cannot allow the kidnappers to get away either," said
Zamora.
</P>
<P>
"We maintain that the hostages' safety is our primary
consideration but we cannot allow the Abu Sayyaf to escape," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The hostages abducted from a Malaysian resort island on April
23 include a Filipino, 10 Malaysians, three Germans, two French
nationals, two South Africans, two Finns, and one Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Zamora sad President Joseph Estrada has spoken to the
representatives of the foreign governments whose nationals were
among the hostages in Sulu to reassure them that Manila is doing
everything to secure the safe release of their citizens.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Press Secretary Ricardo Puno announced that a
delegation of Malaysian officials relayed to the president their
support for the Philippine government's handling of the hostage
situation in Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Puno, who is also the presidential spokesman, has stressed that
the negotiations concerning the release of the hostages are "
basically the function of the Philippine government."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Estrada administration has also
received several "expressions of support" from the other foreign
governments whose nationals are now being held hostage in Sulu.
</P>
</TEXT>
