<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Economic Recovery "Sustainable": Deputy FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIANG MAI (Thailand), May 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economic
recovery will sustain under the support of stable macroeconomic
environment, undergoing key reform programs and broad-based
recovery, said Thai Deputy Finance Minister Pisit Lee-artham here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar organized by the Asian Development Bank (
ADB), Pisit said the pace of Thailand's recovery is "gradual but
firm" with supporting indicators such as continuous growth of
gross domestic products in 1999, increase of production index,
recovery of private consumption and sharp increase in exports.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's economy grew by 4.1 percent in 1999 compared with an
unprecedented plunge of 10.4 percent in 1998, according to ADB
statistics released last week.
</P>
<P>
"This year Thailand's economy is expected to grow by 4.5
percent," Pisit said.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout the crisis, Thailand was able to keep low inflation,
low interest rate, stable exchange rate, lower external debt and
ample foreign exchange reserves and current account surplus," thus
creating a stable macroeconomic environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand also carried out a series of key reform programs in
the past two years, he said, citing the enactment and
implementation of bankruptcy, privatization and real estate laws.
</P>
<P>
Liberalization of foreign entries into economic sectors, good
governance to enhance transparency and accountability and social
and political reforms also helped create a favorable environment
for Thailand's sustainable recovery, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Now a broad-based recovery is underway" in Thailand, Pisit
said, listing three factors such as recovery is shown in
manufacturing, service and export sector; further contribution
will come from new investment as excess capacity is being
exhausted and human and financial resources are reasonable
channeled.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted, there still exist a lot of risks on the
road to sustainable recovery, such as abort or delay of further
reform, huge public sector debt, prolonged private sector
restructuring, slow corporate restructuring and continued low
information technology usage.
</P>
<P>
Thailand needs to press on reform agenda and promote
international competitiveness, which will be a key to sustain
recovery in the globalized world, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 33rd annual meeting of the board of governors of the ADB is
going to be held in this mountainous city, some 1,000 kilometers
north of Bangkok from Saturday to next Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
