<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Deputy Finance Minister Vies for Zanzibar Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Deputy Minister for
Finance Abdisalaam Issa Khatibu Thursday declared his intention to
run for the Zanzibar presidency in the general elections to be
held in October this year, newspapers here reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony held at the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM)'s
headquarters in the central town of Dodoma, Khatibu collected the
presidential nomination forms from CCM Secretary-General Phillip
Mangula after paying the non-refundable fee of 1 million Tanzanian
shillings (about 1,250 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"I reached the decision to run for the Zanzibar Presidency
because I believe that I have all the qualifications. It is my
constitutional right to do so," the 60-year old Member of
Parliament from Makunduchi, Zanzibar, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Khatibu, the first CCM member who joined the race for
Zanzibar's top government position, said he was not pressured by
anyone or group of people to vie for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, Zanzibar's main opposition leader Seif Sharrif
Hamad declared his intention to join the presidential race in the
spicy Isles presidential, general and civic elections in Zanzibar,
which are scheduled to be held on October 29 this year.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar joined with mainland Tanganyika to form the United
Republic of Tanzania after a revolt in 1964 that ousted the Sultan
and Omani Arabs who ruled the Indian Ocean Island. However, it is
a semiautonomous state with
its own government and parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
