<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Acquisition not to Ruin Economy: Zimbabwean Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The compulsory acquisition of some
white-owned commercial farms by the government for resettlement
will not ruin the economy, Zimbabwean Minister of Information,
Posts and Telecommunications Chen Chimutengwende has said.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is that such resettlement will enable the resettled
people to grow enough crops to feed themselves and pay for the
health services and the education of their families," he was
quoted by Friday's daily Herald as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister dismissed British High Commissioner to Zimbabwe
Peter Longworth's assertion in a newspaper article on Wednesday
that Zimbabwe's economy would be destroyed if land was acquired by
the government.
</P>
<P>
The empowering of the people through access to fertile land is
a priority in the country's economic development, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot leave 70 percent of our best arable land located in
areas with good rainfall to 4,000 former Rhodesians who only use
about 25 percent of it. Much of that land is not used at all
while millions of our people are landless," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that after taking the land that has been identified by
the government as suitable for resettlement, there would still be
plenty of room for white commercial farmers who are prepared to
share land with the majority.
</P>
<P>
"Peter Longworth is not saying the truth when he says the
British government has a large amount of money for land reform in
Zimbabwe," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"The recent London land talks proved that it is impossible for
Zimbabwe to access such funds because of the conditions. We need
such funds for compensation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chimutengwende reaffirmed Zimbabwe's position on land that the
British government, which created the land problem in the first
place, would have to pay for compensation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
