<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges Uganda, Rwanda to End Quarrel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has urged
Ugandan President Yoweri President Museveni and his Rwandan
counterpart Paul Kagame to resolve the hostility between the two
countries, the New Vision daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The hostilities between Uganda and Rwanda worry us," Aldo
Ajello, EU special representative to the Great Lakes region, was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I met and talked to Kagame and Museveni. They said that they
are in dialogue. They should stop the nonsense of fighting with
each other," Ajello said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "we shall do our best to prevent any future
conflicts between Uganda and Rwanda."
</P>
<P>
Hostilities and marred relations between the two countries
occurred after the August 1999 clashes between the two armies in
Kisangani, the Democratic Republic Congo (DRC), and the recent
accusations by Rwanda that Uganda was massing troops in the same
area.
</P>
<P>
EU hopes that after the security concerns of Uganda and Rwanda
have been guaranteed, the Uganda Peoples' Defense Forces and the
Rwanda Patriotic Army will leave the DRC, Ajello said.
</P>
<P>
"No one has the legitimacy of occupying another country
forever," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
