<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda not to Plan on Re-opening Kinshasa Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has no urgent
plan so far to re-open its embassy in Kinshasa, capital of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), the New Vision daily
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Re-opening the embassy will need comprehensive discussions,"
Amama Mbabazi, state minister for regional cooperation, was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, "the Kinshasa government in 1998
acted in violation of the Geneva Convention governing diplomatic
missions."
</P>
<P>
Uganda's Embassy in Kinshasa was looted and shut down shortly
after rebellion broke out in the DRC on August 2, 1998. The DRC
government accused Uganda and Rwanda of supporting the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Although the embassy remains physically closed, Uganda has
maintained its diplomatic relations with Kinshasa, Mbabazi said.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni met with Ismail Tutwamoto
Lubenga, DRC minister of State for External Security, at his home
in Rwakitura Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lubenga delivered a special message from President Laurent
Kabila to Museveni, which concerned current efforts to resolve the
conflict in the DRC and the normalization of relations between
Uganda and the DRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
