<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pound Slides After Bank Leaves Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England's Monetary Policy
Committee (MPC) has left base rates unchanged at 6 percent this
month, sending the pound sliding to its lowest level against the
dollar in almost four years.
</P>
<P>
There was sufficient surprise at the no-change verdict to
trigger a switch from sterling to the dollar. The pound dipped to
1.5360 U.S. dollars, its lowest since May 1996, before recovering
to 1.5423 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the move was a reaction to the pound's fresh
gains in recent weeks. Sterling has risen 4.5 percent in trade-
weighted terms since the committee last met.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the euro was only able to make modest ground against
the pound, closing less than 1p firmer at 57.85p. The combination
of the pound's dollar weakness and euro strength is a double blow
for UK manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly all our imported raw materials, including oil, are
priced in dollars, which raises the cost for manufacturers," said
Nick Parsons, chief currency strategist at Commerzbank.
</P>
<P>
Economists generally agreed that when the details of the MPC's
meeting are published in a fortnight's time, they will show that
the pound's relative strength persuaded a majority of the nine
committee members against a rate rise.
</P>
<P>
There was general relief at the MPC's decision, which came on
the same day that the British Bankers' Association announced
record lending to the private sector of 17.3 billion pounds (
around 26.6 billion U.S. dollars) in the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
Industrialists were delighted. The Confederation of British
Industry said: "This was the right decision. It should be seen as
a signal that interest rates have peaked."
</P>
<P>
But in financial markets many believe it is only a matter of
time before the Bank tightens monetary policy further. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
