<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Finance Minister Avraham Shochat Thursday issued an
executive order banning the opening of any new personal savings
plans until transitional tax regulations are approved by the
Knesset (parliament) Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
The order was intended to prevent a mass, last-minute rush by
the public to open tax-free savings plans to avoid paying a 25-
percent tax on savings as proposed in the new tax reform package.
</P>
<P>
The sweeping tax-reform package, prepared by Finance Ministry
Director-General Avi Ben-Bassat and unveiled on Thursday, is
expected to take effect on January 1, 2001, provided it is endorsed
by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Ha'arez
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli cabinet Thursday night authorized a retaliatory
attack on infrastructure in Lebanon after Hezabollah's Katyusha
rockets killed one Israeli solider, wounded about 25 people and
sent about 200,000 residents of the northern Galilee to shelters
earlier in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak reiterated his position at the
cabinet meeting that Israel was not to be trifled with Hezbollah
during the planned pullout from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Washington called on the sides to show restraint and to return
to the Grapes of Wrath understandings of June 1996, when Israel and
Hezbollah agreed to refrain from hitting positions that could cause
civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv
</P>
<P>
-- The tax-reform plan drafted by the Israeli Ben-Bassat
Commission is expected to face a tough battle for approval in the
Knesset (parliament) with both opposition and coalition voicing
displeasure with all or parts of the program on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although Finance Minister Avraham Shochat called for extensive
support for the plan, Knesset members believed he had left some
room for compromise and that the package would not pass a final
vote in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
The tax-reform proposal is expected to reach the Knesset for its
preliminary reading some time next month. Shochat hopes it will be
approved by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Sri Lanka Thursday announced it would resume diplomatic ties
with Israel, and by next week it will send an official delegation
to Israel to establish relations with the Israeli government and
present an urgent request for military aid.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka, which is now fighting against Tamil rebels, has cut
off relations with Israel twice before, once in 1970 and once in
1990 under pressure from the Moslem community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
