<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Kicks off Runoff of Parliamentary Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran kicked off the second round of
the parliamentary election Friday morning despite of the delay by
the conservative Guardians Council to confirm the first round
result in Tehran constituency.
</P>
<P>
The polling started at 0900 a.m. (0430 GMT) in 52 constituencies
in 22 provinces and will last for 10 hours till 0700 p.m.. Some 132
candidates are running for the remaining 66 seats of the 290-seat
Majlis (parliament).
</P>
<P>
The reformist allies of President Mohammad Khatami are believed
to repeat the landslide victory in the February polls though they
are deprived of a voice in the campaign after the conservative
judiciary closed down almost all the mouthpieces of the reformists.
</P>
<P>
The reformists took over more than two thirds of the 224 seats
in the first round, ousting the longtime conservative majority in
parliament that had stymied much of the Khatami's reform programs.
</P>
<P>
However, observers said, the fate of the first round polls in
Tehran constituency will rely on the result of the runoffs as the
election watchdog Guardians Council claimed it had found some
errors in vote counting.
</P>
<P>
The Guardians Council waits to see the result of the runoffs to
decide whether to confirm or nullify the result of Tehran
constituency, the biggest and most important one in which the
reformists had won 29 out of the total 30 seats, political analysts
here said.
</P>
<P>
The council said on Thursday that it had found some errors in
the vote counting and vowed to continue a third recount to remove
riggings.
</P>
<P>
The Guardians Council has nullified the results in 12
constituencies, depriving nine reformists from entering the Majlis
and forcing others to the runoffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
