<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second "Asian Miracle" Foreseeable: Sakakibara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIANG MAI, (Thailand) May 5 (Xinhua) -- The second "Asian
miracle" can be probably achieved in the 21st century if Asian
countries can adapt to the changes brought by information
technology revolution, Eisuke Sakakibara, former vice finance
minister of Japan, said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar organized by the Asian Development Bank (
ADB), Sakakibara, dubbed as "Mr. Yen" for his then influence on
international financial market, expressed positive views on Asia's
economic perspective.
</P>
<P>
"Asia has a great future if we can quickly adapt our economic
and social system to the new environment while building a defense
mechanism to shield us from volatile and sometimes violent swings
in the globalized and virtualized markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
Saying the world is in a period of "great transformations from
old industrial-financial capitalism to what can be called
information or cyber-capitalism," Sakakibara warned Asian
countries to structurally change their economies and societies to
adapt to the new environment.
</P>
<P>
He cited three basic Asia possesses that will help the region
adapt to the IT revolution, which are the high savings ratio, the
high level of primary and secondary education and the sensitivity
and the ability to absorb high technology.
</P>
<P>
"Asia is well placed in the coming years to reap the rewards
of the IT revolution and could catch up with the U.S. in due
course," Sakakibara said.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned, the revolutionary IT transformation of the
world has had its negative side.
</P>
<P>
He pointing out the major cause of the Asian financial crisis
was the failure of crisis-hit countries to properly monitor the
process of transition from industrial capitalism where the state
played some significant guiding role to information capitalism
where the capital flow is free, guided by real time information.
</P>
<P>
He said Asian countries have to be vigilant and quickly create
the defense mechanism to forestall or at least shield them from
the next crisis that could hit them in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The 33rd annual meeting of the board of governors of the ADB is
going to be held in Chiang Mai, a mountainous city some 1,000
kilometers north of Bangkok, from Saturday to next Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
