<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Urged to Intensify Fight Against Tuberculosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 4 (Xinhua) -- A report released Thursday urges
U.S. policy makers to intensify the fight against tuberculosis by
detecting latent infections and strengthening public health
services.
</P>
<P>
The report -- "Ending Neglect: The Elimination of Tuberculosis
in the United States" -- was released by the Institute of Medicine.
It calls for rigorous screening programs targeting high-risk U.S.
communities, especially visa applicants from countries where the
disease is widespread.
</P>
<P>
The number of tuberculosis cases has dropped in the United
States in recent years, but swift action is still needed because a
global epidemic remains a potential source of new infections, the
report said. Some 40 percent of new tuberculosis cases in the
country are among immigrants.
</P>
<P>
"This country has entered a dangerous phase in which the
disease has retreated to specific communities, where it can lie
dormant and resist detection," said Morton N. Swartz, chairman of
the committee writing the report.
</P>
<P>
"Without decisive steps to identify and treat the undetected
cases, the disease could come back with a vengeance and exact a
heavy price," Swartz said.
</P>
<P>
Medical advances led to a fall in U.S. TB case numbers during
the 1960s. In 1972, the Congress eliminated funding dedicated to
fighting the disease. In subsequent years, experts said, many
public-health efforts designed to prevent tuberculosis collapsed,
infection rates rose and deadly drug-resistant strains of the
disease emerged.
</P>
<P>
Recommendations made in the report include improving screening
for latent infections among high-risk groups, reorganizing TB-
control systems to reflect the shifting patterns of the disease,
increasing efforts to assist other countries in fighting the
global epidemic, as well as improving methods for detecting and
treating latent infections as an aggressive strategy to eliminate
the disease in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
