<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Zloty Tumbles to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The Polish zloty on Thursday dropped
to its record low of 4.585 to the U.S. dollar, after reports were
released showing an increase in the current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
Data released by the National Bank of Poland showed that the
deficit reached 1.43 billion U.S. dollars in March, higher than
the expected level between 1.1 billion and 1.3 billion. The
deficit in March accounted for 8.3 percent of the GDP, compared
with 8 percent in February, with a deficit of 954 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The root cause of the deficit increase was slumping exports and
interest payment of foreign loans. Zloty has dropped all the way
since the Polish government completely liberalized the exchange
rates last month.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the Polish zloty can spur exports, but it
can also deal a blow to confidence of foreign investors, according
to Polish economists. A currency crisis is possible as there are
phenomena of panic buying of dollars and underselling of zloty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
