<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Trans Air Inc. to Take Delivery of 47 Boeing Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 4 (Xinhua) -- American Trans Air Inc. (ATA)
announced Thursday it would take delivery of 47 Boeing commercial
jets, including 17 from leasing companies and 30 new planes worth
2 billion U.S. dollars at list prices.
</P>
<P>
Deliveries will begin in May 2001, according to a news release
from ATA, which also has an option for 50 more jets, including 10
757s and 40 737s.
</P>
<P>
The 757-300 lists at 81 million dollars while the 737-800 lists
at 57 million dollars, though airlines typically receive hefty
discounts from catalog prices.
</P>
<P>
The order follows one announced by American Airlines earlier
this week for 20 757-200s, worth about 1.4 billion dollars to the
Seattle-based aerospace giant.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the latest deal would be a significant boost for
Boeing's 757 line.
</P>
<P>
The orders are "a positive shot in the arm for the 757," said
aerospace analyst Robert Toomey of Dain Rauscher-PCG in Seattle. "
There had been some issues regarding the momentum of that product
line, and I think this helps it."
</P>
<P>
The orders make 757 production cutbacks "substantially less
likely, and the rate might even edge up," said Cai von Rumohr of
SG Cowen Securities in Boston.
</P>
<P>
ATA, a unit of Amtran Inc., said it will retire 24 727-200
narrowbodies and six L-1011 widebodies, and will look at buying
widebody jets in 12 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
ATA considered buying A320 and A321 narrowbodies, but chose
Boeing's package, which included financing and investments from
Boeing and aircraft lessors International Lease Financing Corp. (
ILFC) and GE Capital Aviation Services (GECAS).
</P>
<P>
Boeing Capital Corporation (BCC) helped nail down the deal for
the Seattle manufacturer by agreeing to help ATA re-market the 24
727s, which might include modification for use as freighters.
</P>
<P>
"Boeing was extremely creative in resolving some of our issues.
They moved very, very fast throughout the negotiating process,"
ATA Chief Executive John Tague said.
</P>
<P>
Airbus said the European consortium had submitted an "
aggressive" proposal to try to win the ATA deal, but Boeing's
package was cheaper.
</P>
<P>
For ATA, which is the largest operator of commercial and
military passenger charters worldwide, the fleet upgrade will
slash its maintenance and fuel costs and propel it into the top 10
rankings among U.S. airlines, Tague said.
</P>
<P>
The airline expects operating revenues to grow from 1.12
billion dollars in 1999 to 1.4 billion dollars in 2000 and 1.7
billion dollars in 2001, Tague said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
