<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miller Leads Pacers to Enter Semifinals in Eastern Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Reggie Miller scored a career-high
41 points to lead the Pacers Thursday to the fifth and deciding
game victory over the Milwaukee Ducks 96-95 and won their first
round best-of-five series at three wins and two losses.
</P>
<P>
However it was Travis Best who hit the game-winner as
Indianapolis beat the Bucks and clinched the berth of the
semifinals at the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
Miller scored 18 points in the fourth quarter but Indiana
needed a boost from Best, who despite making just 2-of-14 shots up
that point, sank a 3-pointer from the corner with 16.5 seconds
left to lift the Pacers to victory in the first-round series.
</P>
<P>
The Pacers will meet the Philadelphia 76ers in the best-of-
seven semifinals series opening on Saturday in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
The top-seeded Pacers, pressed to the limit by the young Bucks,
needed a big game from Miller, and the sharpshooting veteran
responded by making 15-of-25 shots and saving his best for the
tension-filled fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
The All-Star guard scored 14 of Indiana's 16 points during one
stretch in the final period.
</P>
<P>
"We kept going to him," said Indianapolis coach Larry Bird. "I
don't think it can get better than that. He kept us in it. Reggie
kept making all the shots. It was great playoff basketball. Both
teams played as hard they could."
</P>
<P>
Milwaukee had a chance to tie but Ervin Johnson missed one of
two free throws with 6.2 seconds to go. The Bucks got one last
opportunity after Jalen Rose missed two foul shots with 1.4
seconds left but Ray Allen's long, running 3-pointer was way off.
</P>
</TEXT>
