<HEADLINE> Computer Virus Hits More Australian Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 18,000 Australian
computer users have been hit by the "love bug" virus, Australian
Associated Press reported Friday.  Anti-virus
research company Trend Micro managing director Kenny Liao said at
least ten major corporations in Australia he knew about had been
hit severely.
</P>
<P>
"We can't confirm yet but we estimate this will be much bigger
than the "Melissa" virus which affected ten million computer
systems worldwide in 72 hours," Liao said.
</P>
<P>
The e-mail message "I Love You" is activated once opened. It
then searches for the user's address book and sends itself to
everyone listed.
</P>
<P>
It also has the capability to delete some files.
</P>
<P>
One of the main problems companies faced was the huge volume of
messages the virus was creating leading to systems crashing.
</P>
<P>
The New South Wales state government computer systems have not
been hit so far.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Information Technology Kim Yeadon said
employees were on full alert. He also offered help to the business
and community with information about the virus and details of how
to combat it on a government web page. 
</P>
</TEXT>
