<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legal Action Launched Against Melbourne Aquarium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Australian Associated Press quoted Friday Lawyers as saying
that they filed the necessary papers in the Victorian Supreme
Court late yesterday after health authorities confirmed the
aquarium was the source of the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
So far, 66 cases have been confirmed as Legionnaires' disease
and all the patients had visited the Aquarium. A further 32 people
were reportedly suspected to have the deadly disease while the
death toll remained at two.
</P>
<P>
Acting general manager of the aquarium Tom Smith told reporters
that "Our concern is with the victims - we want to see their best
interests put first."
</P>
<P>
Smith said the aquarium wanted to know how the bacteria got
into the cooling towers of a brand new building and how it can be
prevented from happening again. "If the experience we've been
through can change things and guarantee these things won't happen
into the future, then all this hardship, grief and sadness won't
have been wasted," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
