<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Payton Tops 7th NBA Defensive Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 4 (Xinhua) -- One day after leading Seattle to
a huge playoff victory over the Utah Jazz, SuperSonics guard Gary
Payton was named to the NBA All-Defensive First Team for the
seventh time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Making up the voting panel was the NBA's 29 head coaches, who
were not permitted to vote for players from their own team.
</P>
<P>
Payton produced his first career playoff triple-double -- 35
points, 10 rebounds and 11 assists Wednesday night and helped the
Sonics avoid first-round elimination and force a fifth and
deciding game.
</P>
<P>
The Sonics beat Jazz and set an NBA playoff record for fewest
points allowed in the second quarter, surrendering just seven. The
previous mark was nine by San Antonio against Utah on April 30,
1994.
</P>
<P>
Payton is just the sixth player in NBA history to be selected
for the All-Defensive First Team at least seven times.
</P>
<P>
He joins an elite group which is headed by Michael Jordan (nine
times), and includes Bobby Jones (8), Scottie Pippen (8), Walt
Frazier (7) and Dennis Rodman (7).
</P>
<P>
Together with Payton on the 1999-2000 team of defensive
standouts is Los Angeles Lakes guard Kobe Bryant, Miami Heat
center Alonzo Mourning, Minnesota Timberwolves forward Kevin
Garnett and San Antonio Spurs forward Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
Payton led all players with 24 First Team votes and was named
on a maximum 28 ballots, garnering 52 of a possible 56 points from
coaches whose best players often had to go up against the fiery
Seattle guard.
</P>
<P>
Mourning came in second in the balloting. The imposing Miami
center was named on 26 ballots and received 42 points.
</P>
<P>
This marks the second selection to the All-Defensive First Team
for both Duncan and Mourning. Bryant and Garnett are being honored
for the first time each.
</P>
<P>
The NBA All-Defensive Second Team consists of Portland's
Scottie Pippen and Clifford Robinson of Phoenix at forward, Lakers
center Shaquille O'Neal and guards Eddie Jones of Charlotte and
Jason Kidd of Phoenix.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
