<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Pct GDP Growth Set for Next Fiscal in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The targeted growth is 0.5 percent higher than the expected 5.5
percent growth of GDP at the end of the current fiscal (1999-2000),
and the size of the next ADP will be around 170 billion taka (3.3
billion U.S. dollars), 15 billion taka (300 million dollars)
higher than the current ADP.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Planning Mohiuddin Khan Alamgir told the
newspaper that the coming ADP will include 200 new projects,
emphasizing the implementation of both the new and the old
projects.
</P>
<P>
He said the new ADP would give priority to four sectors,
including primary education, rural roads and telecommunications,
rural electrification and rural health-care services.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the implementation of the current ADP, the state
minister said 54 percent of the program under the ADP for the
current fiscal had been implemented, and the success ratio in
project implementation is the highest in last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
He, however, admitted that some foreign-aided projects could
not be implemented as the aid so far was not available due to
various reasons.
</P>
<P>
The government envisaged 65.26 billion taka (1.25 billion
dollars)as project aid in the current ADP, which was 41 percent of
the total ADP.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,293 projects had been taken under current ADP by
giving priority to education, poverty eradication, human resources
development, flood rehabilitation and improvement of social
services.
</P>
</TEXT>
