<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Rooting Out Drug Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Myanmar official has
called for rooting out narcotic drug problem in the country,
saying that the problem is an evil legacy left behind by the "
colonialists".
</P>
<P>
At an annual meeting of the Myanmar Central Committee for Drug
Abuse Control (CCDAC) here Thursday, Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt,
first secretary of the country's State Peace and Development
Council, said the problem is still being used by old and neo-"
colonialists" to get political benefit in disparaging Myanmar,
official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
He noted the government is trying to totally eradicate narcotic
drugs as a national task as the problem not only tarnishes the
image of the nation and social norms but also threatens the entire
mankind on the earth.
</P>
<P>
He charged that at present, some of the big "neo-colonialist"
countries, instead of rendering assistance to Myanmar's drug
elimination efforts, are exploiting the country's drug problem to
their political advantages and making fabricated accusations
against Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
In wiping out the problem of narcotic drugs, Myanmar not only
applies control and eradication method but also strives for
development of the areas where poppy was once grown, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for efforts to launch narcotic drug eradication
campaigns in the country in cooperation with agencies of the
United Nations, friendly countries and Southeast Asian family
nations to pass on correct information in countering the
fabrications spread by those from inside and outside the country
who are trying to gain political advantages by exploiting the drug
problem.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for developing country like Myanmar to
make harmonious and concerted efforts for drug eradication on
their own under the condition with insufficient technology,
equipment and strong financial backing.
</P>
<P>
He urged departments concerned to successfully carry out the
tasks of CCDAC with the aim of wiping off the soil and waters of
Myanmar's problem of narcotic drugs, the legacy of "colonialists",
which is casting shadow over the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
