<HEADLINE> Swedish Deputy PM Hails Relations With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Ties between Sweden and China have
been developing steadily during the past 50 years, and bilateral
exchanges in trade, industry, science and culture have produced
inspiring fruit, Swedish Deputy Prime Minister Lena Hjelm-wallen
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At a reception hosted by Chinese Ambassador to Sweden Wang
Guisheng to celebrate the 50th anniversary of official diplomatic
ties between the two countries, Hjelm-wallen added that trade
between the two countries has always been "mutually beneficial"
and China has become Sweden's second largest trading partner in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister said she felt happy that she will
lead a delegation to China to attend similar celebrations for the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador said that relations between the two
countries have been growing rapidly during the past five decades,
particularly during the past 20 years since China adopted the
policy of opening-up and reform.
</P>
<P>
History has shown that it is in the interests of the two
peoples to develop Sino-Swedish relations, and China is willing to
work together with Sweden to push their bilateral relations to a
higher level in the 21st century, he added.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Trade Minister Leif Pagrotsky and Environment Minister
Kjell Larsson, among other government officials and dignitaries,
attended the reception. 
</P>
