<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Demilitarized Zone Exists for Kosovo: Yugoslav Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav military on Thursday
refuted the remarks made recently by a U.S. general that there
exists "a demilitarized zone" along the border between the
troubled Kosovo province and the rest of Yugoslavia's Serbian
Republic.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to Kosovo, Henry Shelton, chairman of the U.S.
Joint Chiefs of Staff, said NATO commander has the right to send
troops to "the demilitarized zone" on Kosovo's border with Serbia
proper.
</P>
<P>
The General Staff of Yugoslavia's armed forces said in a
statement that there does not exist such a demilitarized zone.
</P>
<P>
Under a military technical accord signed last June between NATO
and Yugoslavia, a five-kilometer-wide security zone was set up
along Kosovo's border with the rest of Serbia, which makes up
Yugoslavia together with Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
The zone is not under the administration of NATO and the NATO-
led peacekeeping force, known as the KFOR, is not entitled to
enter the area, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that it is the United Nations, not NATO,
that is governing the province. By making such a statement, it
added, the U.S. four-star army general was trying to deny the
basic views contained in relevant United Nations resolutions and
the military technical accord.
</P>
<P>
Such a groundless and willful move will neither help implement
the U.N. Security Council's Resolution 1244 and the military
technical accord, nor will it help restore stability in Kosovo,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
KFOR entered Kosovo last June following the withdrawal of
Yugoslav troops from the province after a 78-day NATO air campaign
against the country. The province has since been under the
administration of a U.N. special mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
