<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 9 in Earthquake in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Death toll rose to nine in a strong
earthquake in Central Sulawesi, Indonesia, on Thursday, according
to reports reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Nine people were killed in the quake while several others
suffered injuries," said Mudjianto, an official at the Meteorology
and Geophysics Agency in Palu, capital of Central Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
Six of the deceased were residents of Peleng island while the
other three were from Luwuk Banggai regency in mainland Central
Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
Mudjianto admitted details of all the victims were not yet
available, saying that administration officials were now visiting
the scene.
</P>
<P>
A tectonic earthquake measuring 6.5 on the Richter scale jolted
the Banggai islands on Thursday noon. It was reported that the
quake centered at 1.36 degrees southern latitude, 123.57 degrees
eastern longitude and 33 kilometers beneath sea level.
</P>
<P>
"The quake shook across the Sulawesi, but the worst happened in
central Sulawesi, especially Luwuk Banggai regency," the
Meteorology and Geophysics Agency's Makassar office head Sunaryo
was quoted by the Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sunaryo said the continuation of the quake might occur, but it
would not as big as the beginning.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of houses in seven subdistricts in Banggai were
reportedly flattened.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the provincial administration Longkyu Janggolo
said tsunami up to six meters in height swept Luwuk and Peleng
island, forcing hundreds of people to flee.
</P>
<P>
"People who lost their homes are now temporarily taking shelter
in tents set up by local administration staff, and we have
supplied them with rice and medicines," Longky said.
</P>
<P>
In Luwuk, some 607 kilometers east of Palu, a pier was
seriously damaged, tens of houses collapsed, and a market burned
down due to a short circuit.
</P>
<P>
The Banggai islands and Banggai district -- some 1,080
kilometers northeast of Jakarta -- have a combined population of
some 600,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
