<HEADLINE> Colombian Children Demand Release of Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, May 4 (Xinhua) -- About a million children and
teenagers from private schools paraded on streets in Colombia's
main cities on Thursday demanding the release of minor hostages
and an end to violence against children and young people.
</P>
<P>
The largest demonstrations were held in downtown avenues in the
capital city of Bogota and Cali, a city in southwestern Colombia,
where nine-year-old student Dagoberto Ospina, leader of student
campaigns for peace in the country, was kidnapped last week.
</P>
<P>
Ospina was forcibly taken from the "Alferez Real" college
school bus by three persons who carried weapons and grenades, in a
kidnapping that has greatly disturbed inhabitants of the city.
</P>
<P>
Class in nearly 5,000 private schools was suspended for
students to attend the peaceful demonstrations, which were called
by the National Confederation of Education Centers.
</P>
<P>
In Cali, the procession was more than five kilometers long,
with students holding placards reading "Release Dagoberto" and "
We want to play and be with our friends."
</P>
<P>
Residents in Cali also demanded the release of Carlos Alberto
Bernal, also a student, who was kidnapped together with his two
schoolmates more than a month ago by the National Liberation Army
guerrillas. His two classmates have already been set free.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Colombian government has pledged to take drastic
steps against kidnapping rampant in the country.
</P>
<P>
About 60 children were abducted during the first three months
of this year, up one-third from 1999, according to the independent
anti- kidnapping group Pais Libre.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian government reported 2,945 kidnappings for last
year and accused the various groups of guerrillas of the
kidnappings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
