<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, May 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A U.S. House of Representatives panel approved a
legislation on Thursday that will lift sanctions on sales of food
and medicine to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, which is added to an agricultural spending
bill, would license such sales so long as they are not subsidized
by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
The measure, passed by a voice vote in a subcommittee of the
House Appropriations Committee, also would prohibit the president
from including food and medicine in future embargoes of other
countries without congressional approval. (US-Cuba-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council on
Thursday urged all parties concerned in Afghanistan, in particular
the Taliban, to resume negotiations under the auspices of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council stressed that the negotiations should be
resumed without further delay and any preconditions in full
compliance with all the relevant U.N. resolutions.(UN-Afganistan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Thursday that it was
considering ways to support the U.N. peacekeeping mission in
Sierra Leone but would not prepare to send ground troops there
after rebels killed U.N. soldiers there.
</P>
<P>
"We're prepared to consider ways to support the U.N. and make
sure the U.N. out there can do its job," said State Department
spokesman Richard Boucher. (US-UN-Sierra Leone)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Thursday adopted a
presidential statement, voicing its strongest condemnation of "the
armed attacks perpetrated by the Revolutionary United Front"
against the U.N. peacekeepers in Sierra Leone, and their "
continued detention of a large number of United Nations and other
international personnel." (UN-Sierra Leone)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- International donors pledged Thursday to issue almost
453 million dollars over the next few months to help with
Mozambique's reconstruction after disastrous flooding.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Undersecretary Rino Serri said that the success
of Thursday's conference between the donors and the Maputo
government lay in "the great ability with which Mozambique
presented itself to the conference, with rigorous analyses and
very serious and well- founded proposals." (Mozambique-Aid)
</P>
