<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IPU Session Ends with Calls for Peace, Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The 103rd conference of the Inter-
Parliamentary Union (IPU) was concluded here on Friday with final
resolutions calling for intensified international efforts for peace
and stability, dialog between different cultures and civilizations
as well as protection of the rights of refugees.
</P>
<P>
During six days of debates, the majority of the participants
agreed that the world is moving toward a multipolar system since
the end of the Cold War, with peace and development as the dominant
trend.
</P>
<P>
But they also agreed that the world is far from tranquil, due to
various conflicts of political, economic, racial and religious
origins.
</P>
<P>
Most delegates from developing countries called for a new and
just world political and economic order to solve international and
regional disputes through dialog, to bridge the gap between the
rich and the poor and to remove the disparity in economic
development.
</P>
<P>
In one of the final resolutions on peace and stability, the IPU
echoed the call of developing countries on parliaments in the world
to promote dialog and foster friendly ties between countries in
political, economic and cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
It also called for an equitable distribution of wealth between
countries, and called on the World Bank and other international
banking institutions to support poverty alleviation programs in
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In a second resolution, the IPU called on its member parliaments
to play a more active role in promoting dialog between different
cultures and civilizations, and take measures to promote cultural
diversity and protect minority cultures in their own countries by
means of legislation.
</P>
<P>
It called for more attention to equal rights between men and
women in political and economic lives, and to the rights of
children to education.
</P>
<P>
The IPU also took up the refugee issue as one of its major
themes at the conference.
</P>
<P>
In a third resolution on refugees, the IPU stressed that rights
of refugees displaced by war and occupation should be fully
respected.
</P>
<P>
It said it fully supports the rights of Palestinian refugees to
return to their homeland. It was seen as an apparent victory for
the Arab bloc of parliamentarians during their debates with their
Israeli counterparts and Israel's supporters.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are over 3 million Palestinian refugees in
Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and other countries, who had fled their
homes during successive Arab-Israeli wars in the past half century.
</P>
<P>
The IPU also stressed that it supports all efforts that could
lead to a just, durable and comprehensive peace in the Middle East,
and said it also supports the "land for peace" principle guiding
the peace process between Israel and its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The conference was opened here on Sunday by Jordanian King
Abdullah Bin Hussein, and its next session is expected to be held
in October in Jakarta, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The IPU, founded in 1889 and now with 144 members, is the
largest international parliamentary organization, and its biannual
conference serves as the biggest venue for parliamentary diplomacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
