<DOCNO> XIE20000505.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Not to Increase Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Mexico will not increase its oil
production during the next two months, despite pressures exerted
in the international market to make the price of crude descend
even more, said the Energy Ministry of this country on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the agreement related to the price of
crude made with Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Norway, would continue
until June 30.
</P>
<P>
Mexico will maintain this position, despite the United States
blackmail against the crude producing nations, with the firm
conviction that the price will be maintained above the 20 dollars
per barrel during the upcoming summer.
</P>
<P>
Mexico raised its oil output from April 1 by 125,000 barrels a
day after two years of the adoption of an agreement with the other
three countries, which made it recover in 1999 the international
prices of the product.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that after this determination taken jointly
with the oil producing countries, a renegotiation will be achieved
as a formula to prevent new jumps or "rebounds" that will take
again the quotations down the undesirable slide.
</P>
<P>
It said that with the present very low levels of inventories,
anything might send the prices soaring, and for that reason Saudi
Arabia, Venezuela, and Mexico have said that a bigger flow of oil
in the market is necessary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
