<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British, Irish PMs Intensify N.Irish Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern were to keep talking with
Northern Ireland's main political parties as efforts to break the
peace process deadlock intensified.
</P>
<P>
The decision to keep talking has been taken after a day of
hectic activity at the venue, Hillsborough Castle, south of
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he believed there was a genuine desire by the
parties involved to move the process forward.
</P>
<P>
He admitted it would not be easy but insisted the will to make
things work was still there.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously the terms have got to be right for all parties but I
think the desire to get it done is very strong," he said.
</P>
<P>
His comments followed a second day of talks which involved Sinn
Fein, Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) and the Ulster
Unionist Party.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman confirmed that Blair spoke by telephone
with U.S. President Bill Clinton to update him about the talks on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Both Blair and Ahern were in Hillsborough for meetings with the
pro-agreement parties.
</P>
<P>
They met the smaller pro-agreement parties on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Since Northern Ireland devolution was suspended on February 11,
both governments' meetings with the parties have been overshadowed
by an unbroken impasse between the Ulster Unionists and Sinn Fein
over IRA arms and power sharing.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams and SDLP leader John Hume both
called on the prime minister to restore the power-sharing
institutions before their party delegations held separate meetings
with Blair and Ahern.
</P>
<P>
Blair should make it clear he is restoring the institutions and
going ahead with the forward implementation of this agreement,"
said Adams.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Hillsborough, leader of the Ulster Unionists David
Trimble said he was still waiting to hear from republicans that
they will decommission their weapons.
</P>
<P>
"The question was put to them by Seamus Mallon (SDLP) in
January when he said 'Tell us if you're going to do it, tell us
when you're going to do it. What we're saying in the same spirit
is tell us what you're prepared to do," he said.
</P>
<P>
No-one was expecting a breakthrough before the "deadline" of
May 22, by which date, according to the Good Friday Agreement, all
parties should have made their best efforts to ensure
decommissioning takes place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
