<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rose on bargain-
hunting Friday as investors ignored more signs of hot U.S. economy
which could prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates
again.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 165.37 at 10,577.86 and
the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 96.58 at 3,816.82.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index rose 23.06 at 1,432.63.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rose as investors moved into the market for bargain-
hunting in defiance of a government report on a lower
unemployment rate in April. Despite the rally, The Dow index
finished the week with a loss of 156.05 points and the Nasdaq
composite fell 43.84 points during the week.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported today that the U.S. unemployment
rate fell to 3.9 percent in April, hitting the lowest level in 30
years while average hourly earnings rose 0.4 percent in the same
month, twice as fast as expectations. Analysts believed the report
will make the Federal Reserve aggressive in raising rates.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised rates five times since last June
to keep inflation under control and more hike in rates is sure to
come at its policymaking meeting on May 16.
</P>
<P>
Investors' concerns about inflation and higher interest rates
had dragged stocks lower in sessions this week.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 6.86 at 638.33 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 7.64 at 928.69. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 10.94 at 512.84.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,675 up, 1,276 down and 475
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 796.33 million shares from 909.89
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
